I think it is not be possible to split this change up into two as, it will enforce us to go ahead with solution 1 (to store console sessions in memory) which creates issues as eventlet module is monkeypatched.

commit_message:
Limits number of console for an instance

Allowing spawning multiple consoles for an instance on
noVNC server can lead to service interruption or disruption.

Closes-Bug: #1227575

DocImpact: Adds console_max_count flag to limit number of
           consoles for an instance (default=3).

Change-Id: If9afb3a9d7febc220b0d4c5c6c28586f88a089f5

commit_message:
Add missing foreign keys in table PCI devices

This patch is to add foreign keys (compute_node_id -> compute_nodes.id)
and (instance_uuid -> instance.uuid) into table PCI devices.

Change-Id: Ie33d236c4b68a1d58fc3fd2b53e932307ab257a0

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-21 12:38:52.000000000', 'message': 'Allowing InternalClient to reuse existing app, withot loading a new app from configuration

Background: InternalClient class of swift/common/internal_client.py is used to generate
internal Swift requests. For example, if a proxy middleware need to perform additional
internal request to Swift this can be easily achieved via InternalClass.

Current state: The InternalClient's __init__ method has a mandatory parameter "conf_path",
that is used by InernalClient to load a new app. However, any proxy middleware already
contains an app, filled during __init__ method of that middleware.
In certain cases a middleware may want to send internal request re-using the same app
as it already has, without forcing InternalClient to load a new app,
that may waste resources and consume some time.

Suggestion: The __init__ method of InternalClass will have additional optional
parameter existing_app=None. If this parameter is supplied, then InternalClass
will use this one without loading a new app from conf_path.

Change-Id: I611e9346fac6d414a9640a823cb29e750605730f
'}, {'created': '2013-11-23 05:52:35.000000000', 'message': 'Allowing InternalClient to reuse existing app.

commit_message:
Allowing InternalClient to reuse existing app.

Background: InternalClient class of swift/common/internal_client.py is used to generate
internal Swift requests. For example, if a proxy middleware need to perform additional
internal request to Swift this can be easily achieved via InternalClass.

Current state: The InternalClient's __init__ method has a mandatory parameter "conf_path",
that is used by InernalClient to load a new app. However, any proxy middleware already
contains an app, filled during __init__ method of that middleware.
In certain cases a middleware may want to send internal request re-using the same app
as it already has, without forcing InternalClient to load a new app,
that may waste resources and consume some time.

Suggestion: The __init__ method of InternalClass will have additional optional
parameter existing_app=None. If this parameter is supplied, then InternalClass
will use this one without loading a new app from conf_path.

Change-Id: I611e9346fac6d414a9640a823cb29e750605730f

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw?

Closes-Bug: #1255856

Change-Id: I22b6fa351dd5b654783f432c01785c706acd8397

commit_message:
catch OSError in (account|container).server

We now uses common.utils.ismount in mount_check and that is excepted to
return True, False or raise OSError. Catching the raising error in
(account|container).server would help to produce a specific response .

Change-Id: I2bfd7a18d3417cce37d23e5702ccf908a4c2f472

commit_message:
Add contextual markers to BatchAction messages

BatchAction message is used for both present (table action menu)
and past (completion message) and there is no way that translators
use different texts for present and passt messages.
This commit add contextual markers to the message strings and allows
translators to use different texts for message in BatchAction.

Change-Id: Ie6438730386fc2cca18704354d5cf5f5b71cd494
Closes-Bug: #1252082
(cherry picked from commit 9e6d59bc8b7811622e42ebdcb5911eb6487a4f77)

Within the scope of a single method, keeping all the reads and writes within
the context managed by a single session. In this way, the session's __exit__
handler will take care of calling flush() and commit() for you.
If using this approach, you should not explicitly call flush() or commit().
See http://stackoverflow.com/questions/4201455/sqlalchemy-whats-the-

"}]
commit_message:
Don't need session.flush in context managed by session

Within the scope of a single method, keeping all the reads and writes within
the context managed by a single session. In this way, the session's __exit__
handler will take care of calling flush() and commit() for you.
If using this approach, you should not explicitly call flush() or commit().
See http://stackoverflow.com/questions/4201455/sqlalchemy-whats-the-
difference-between-flush-and-commit

Closes-Bug: #1258044
Change-Id: I53f7a054ffd4a4d72ae20d5efc91bc24c1f7516e

@nikhil, interesting question but why Jenkins tests are ok here this time? any thoughts? So I think code is ok IMO.'}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2013-11-15 06:09:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Zhi yeah!, you know it's the strangest thing that it seems to work fine locally on the development boxes (ubuntu/ubuntu server/fedora19 server for me) and fails intermittently on jenkins. I'm sure you can find more imports in glance (and openstack in general which use the "as" option).

My best guess at this point is that there is some weirdness in the python interpreter that is used on some of the jenkins infrastructure. (It's not related to py26 or py27 - is what we've observed) However, it may be the variation in distros that might make the difference. I'm not sure :/'}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2013-11-18 17:45:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

After talking with Alex offline, he pointed out that that this might happen in cases when there is import within the same namespace twice:

for example:

...
    import a.b.c
    import a.b.c.d as e
...

might be an issue

however, just

...
    import a.b.c.d as e
...

should be fine.'}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-11-18 19:02:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Move is_image_sharable to registry api

When using the membership kwarg in is_image_sharable with the sqlalchemy driver,
an AttributeError may be raised since the 'member' variable is not always
defined. This function was copied throughout the db drivers and untested.

This patch adds tests and moves the function to the v1 registry api, where it
was the only place being used. Tests for this function in test_context were
removed as it does not make sense to test this function there and allowed for
the removal of the membership kwarg.

Fixes bug 1247481

Change-Id: Ia77bc0a144831ddcf7e180afdb0842754ff3fcf2

commit_message:
Change to improve dhcp-agent sync_state

Added a pool.waitall to dhcp-agent sync_state
to ensure that the last pool of threads are complete
before another sync_state begins.  Added another
log message to aid in debugging. Also added the
test_sync_state_waitall unit test.

Change-Id: I13d79a212672c4086e3082783743cb1ef2b48cfb
Closes-Bug: #1257514

commit_message:
Fix HEAD tempurls

HEAD-only tempurls didn't work; tempurl only allowed a HEAD request if
the tempurl was generated for GET or PUT (that is, the method in the
HMAC-signed string was "GET" or "PUT").

The intent of the code was to allow a user with a GET or a PUT tempurl
to also perform a HEAD request; I think the breaking of HEAD tempurls
is just a bug.

Change-Id: I621ddaac03e0d058dd9e7c7c374cb5c4b6386d36

commit_message:
Add extra extension file to makemessage command line

specify the file extensions of the makemessage to *.html, *.txt, *.csv

Closes-Bug: #1226910
(cherry picked from commit 0b03a7fdea3d6586ec2c22783e309bb75d68fdc5)

The above fix introduces an extra bug when updating POT files, so
the commit below is also cherry-picked.
----
Fix warning in run_tests.sh --makemessages

Specify --extension=html,txt,csv only for openstack_dashboard.
For djangojs, --extension should be 'js'.
This is the cause of the warning.

Closes-Bug: #1243526
(cherry picked from commit 79ae2139bb2f458de698aa116270428f54e22dc6)
----

This patch does not update POT files for stable/havana.
They will be updated in a single patch.

Change-Id: I115cd448249ac0b1b27a6b28fca3f16d6b2670a6

commit_message:
create a horizon exercise for sanity check

from time to time horizon gets broken in devstack and it
takes a while to figure out why. Put a sanity check into
devstack exercises that checks for horizon front page being
up and not just a stack trace to use as a simple gate.

Change-Id: I13a6c59881f618d5194b1625b67115013c9cb6c2

commit_message:
Use six.iteritems to make dict work on Python2/3

six.iteritems returns an iterator over dictionarys items.
This replaces dictionary.iteritems() on Python 2 and dictionary.items()
on Python 3. See http://pythonhosted.org/six/#six.iteritems

Implements: blueprint make-python3-compatible
Change-Id: I90be87979ebc7eccd11d66cd1eef16d9b2eb9fda

commit_message:
Remove comments from empty __init__.py files

We have quite a few __init__.py files that will fail the new hacking
rule "H104: File contains nothing but comments".
These need to be cleaned up.

Closes-bug: 1258355

Change-Id: I4cb3f66f97c3807a69293aad47a671c48adbb1d8

commit_message:
Enable cluster deployment with pre-installed JDK

This commit is the first one in a series to support cluster deployment
for VMs with no external access (e.g. access to package repositories).
This commit supports the ability to specify to Ambari that a JDK already
exists in the specified location.  Therfore, the JDK download from a
potentially external location will be prevented and the existing JDK
pre-installed on the VM image will be leveraged.

The full disconnected facility still depends on the following (which will
be addressed in subsequent commits):

- additional testing
- an updated HDP image with the full set of required packages
- a fix to an ambari issue with nagios installation discovered
during testing

partially implements blueprint hdp-specify-local-repo

Change-Id: I36fb109225c6ea21114d7e80e7d3ce950ad0b6a7

commit_message:
heat engine changes for abandon-stack

abandon-stack operation is similar to delete-stack, but actual
resources would not be deleted. Only stack and resource data
would be deleted from heat database. And also abandon-stack
operation would return the stack/resources data in json format.

Implements: blueprint abandon-stack
Change-Id: Ibb386255887d4de54e9a3dc95254a7151475cf3a

commit_message:
Support a new qpid topology

There has been a bug open for a while pointing out that the way we
create direct exchanges with qpid results in leaking exchanges since
qpid doesn't support auto-deleting exchanges.  This was somewhat
mitigated by change to use a single reply queue.  This meant we created
far fewer direct exchanges, but the problem persists anyway.

A Qpid expert, William Henry, originally proposed a change to address
this issue.  Unfortunately, it wasn't backwards compatible with existing
installations.  This patch takes the same approach, but makes it
optional and off by default.  This will allow a migration period.

As a really nice side effect, the Qpid experts have told us that this
change will also allow us to use Qpid broker federation to provide HA.

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1178375
Co-authored-by: William Henry <whenry@redhat.com>

(cherry picked from commit 76972e2949634abe9fcc9ad36c103cca94300237)

Conflicts:
	tests/unit/rpc/test_qpid.py

Change-Id: I09b8317c0d8a298237beeb3105f2b90cb13933d8

Add config for amqp durable/auto_delete queues

This patch makes two new config options (amqp_durable_queues and
amqp_auto_delete) that enable durable and auto delete queues in amqp.

Fixes: bug #1033915

(cherry picked from commit 5ff534d15a136decd6d076fc1f2cd066806843c9)

commit_message:
Build mirror using proper requirements.

* tools/integration.sh: Use the --no-update flag to run-mirror to make
sure that the repo checked out by devstack-gate is the repo used to
build the mirror. Otherwise `git reset --hard remote/origin/master` is
used which we do not want.

Change-Id: I3c99c96bfd6d7502ab7582131a57baa4a8d27a66

commit_message:
Force d2to1 into the integration test mirror.

* tools/integration.sh: We can't update the requirements repo until
integration.sh is working and for that we need to install d2to1 into the
mirror. Usually this would require a requirements repo change, but
chicken and egg. Force it in along with pip and setuptools instead. This
can be removed when d2to1 is added to the requirements repo.

Change-Id: I26690ea8aa42d004c47692f5c28030c389fa1be9

commit_message:
Build mirror using proper requirements.

* tools/integration.sh: Use the --no-update flag to run-mirror to make
sure that the repo checked out by devstack-gate is the repo used to
build the mirror. Otherwise `git reset --hard remote/origin/master` is
used which we do not want. Also, we can't update the requirements repo
until integration.sh is working and for that we need to install d2to1
into the mirror. Usually this would require a requirements repo change,
but chicken and egg. Force it in along with pip and setuptools instead.
This can be removed when d2to1 is added to the requirements repo.

Change-Id: Id5c2c902832e475f28310fdd547672464bf42c0c

commit_message:
Fixed a failing test on my saio

The added sleep makes this test pass on my saio. I have not heard of
it failing for anyone else, but I figured I'd post this up just in
case someone does have the same problem and this fixes it for them.

Change-Id: Ia0bb09d36d0b531ade7c6a6034bbe31dd6c90a98

In method downgrade_cisco in migration folsom_initial instead of
local method drop_tables op.drop_tables is used

commit_message:
Catch ImageBusy exception when deleting rbd volume

If we try to delete an rbd volume that has 'watchers' on it
i.e. client connections that have not yet been closed
possibly because a client crashed, the remove() will throw an
ImageBusy exception. We now catch this exception and raise
VolumeIsBusy with a useful message.

If the volume delete fails in this way it will now stay as
'available' instead of going to 'error_deleting' so that the
delete can be retried (since it is expected to work on a
retry after waiting for the connection to timeout).

Change-Id: I5bc9a5f71bdb0f9c5d12b5577e68377e66561f5b
Closes-bug: 1256259

commit_message:
Create a shared queue for QPID topic consumers

When multiple RPC servers (consumers) are subscribed to the same RPC
topic, a single RPC request to that topic should be received by only
one of the consumers.  A bug in the QPID driver caused every consumer
to receive a copy of the RPC request.  This bug affects only Topology
version 2.  This patch will cause a single queue to be created for
each topic, and shared among all consumers of that topic.  This
results in each RPC request being received by only one consumer,
in turn across all the competing consumers.

Closes-Bug: #1257293
Change-Id: Id6af86f7fb536f3caff50bec4d5fde8a3ac1e83a

'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-11-28 01:01:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

see "5" https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/solum-api-spec-review'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-11-28 01:07:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

there is a discussion on the ml about projects/tenants and Steven Hardy suggested:
"why do the APIs requests have to contain the project ID at all?  Isn't that something we derive from the token in
auth_token (setting X-Project-Id, which we use to set the project in the request context)?"

I agree with this for incoming requests, but we still need this info on outputted resources. - this is going to get messy, as we will have multiple serialization classes for each type (ComponentInput, ComponetOutput) - and that kind of sucks.'}, {'account_id': 8334, 'date': '2013-11-28 03:24:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 9124, 'date': '2013-12-03 17:47:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2013-12-05 00:23:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

If we want to track resource ownership, wouldn't it be more natural to define it as part of the "path" of a resource (e.g.: /<project-id>/<user-id>/assemblies/, rather than putting it in the serialized object representation of a resource?'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-12-05 06:22:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Openstack as a whole is moving away from that pattern. for a number of reasons. You have to create a lot of paths for every object type to describe users, projects and domains. also we still need this as when an admin gets multiple objects belonging to a range of users the admin would want to see who owns the object.'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2013-12-05 07:11:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-12-05 16:16:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

looks like this needs a rebase"}, {'account_id': 9094, 'date': '2013-12-05 17:20:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Apologies if I missed a previous discussion about this but I don't understand why product_id and user_id would be sent from Solum to the user.  I can't imagine a scenario where a Solum user would send these fields because Solum would need to verify the authentication token anyways before taking any action (user_id or project_id could be spoofed).  That token should tie into user and project information either in a Keystone database or Solum control plane database I would image.

My understanding is that entities in the data model (like assemblies and components) would have links to other related entities in the system which can be used to navigate."}, {'account_id': 9095, 'date': '2013-12-05 17:33:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

These ID's don't belong in the API controller classes. The resources defined in the controller classes are the data model seen by the user.

Take a look at the API worker blue print here. https://blueprints.launchpad.net/solum/+spec/api-worker-architecture

The blueprint defines a controller -> dispatcher -> handler  architecture. All resources (assemblies, components, etc) will be defines at the handler layer again, and will include fields for internal use by Solum, such as these ID's.

Basically, we need two data models, one which is returned to the user as responses and one that corresponds directly with the DB data model, which will include fields such as these ID's which are used internally."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-05 19:16:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-05 19:22:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

So, I'm going to be vigorously in favour here. The API design concept of hiding data from the API means hiding it from ops as well. And this is bad. For instance, from #openstack-infra where we have a team that operate APIs like gerrit:

08:19 < clarkb> lifeless: that is what gerrit does :)
08:20 < clarkb> and it is painful
08:20 < fungi> we hateses it

I'm very happy to help figure out a way to address the concerns that that hiding is meant to accomplish, but forcing ops to log into the DB to recover things is deeply problematic."}, {'account_id': 9095, 'date': '2013-12-05 19:58:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Designing an API which does not hide anything would mean users of the platform would see everything Ops sees when they query a resource. Ops does not need to log into the DB to get these IDs. We can expose a different API, used by an admin tool for example, which exposes everything to Ops.'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2013-12-05 20:05:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I suggest we avoid the temptation to discuss a separate admin API. I think filtering of output, limiting of scope, and access control should be implemented using RBAC and the use of tenants for scoping. I see no harm in tagging resources with identifiers. The more visible the ownership of resources is, the easier Solum will be to support when it comes to diagnosing issues.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-12-05 20:27:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

commit_message:
WIP: attempt to see if changing queue names makes parallel work

this is a crazy experiment to see if just changing the queue names
to be non overlapping is all that's needed for parallel. Mostly
because getting zmq tests to work locally was a fail, so see what
the check queue thinks. If this looks promissing a more complete
patch (and better commit message) will come later.

Change-Id: I46eec5977729ac2565d7e20a8c35ded9df5fdf36

commit_message:
The core part of GCE API addition to nova.

It contains changed configuration files, README, unit tests, and the code. Code consists of:
wsgi.py service framework,
common.py with base controller and common stuff,
base_api.py with base API abstraction - descendants implement specific parts of GCE API functionality by means of using corresponding OpenStack functionality,
zones.py and zone_api.py - Zones functionality controller and API implementation correspondingly,
api.py, api-gce.py, service.py with necessary changes to add a new nova API.

This commit is stripped of all of the GCE API functionality except for Zones for simplification reasons. Next commits will bring additional functional parts.
Besides unit tests for each functional parts there is an integral Tempest test which will be contributed later along with functionality parts.

Change-Id: I9139806e1416657991304480df5189ffbcb62614
Implements: blueprint gce-api

commit_message:
Use stevedore for plugins loading

Stevedore is the common approach to load plugins in OpenStack. It
provides extremely much more options than current handmade plugins
loader. We'll need it espessially for implementing pluggable resources
provisioning code.

In addition, setting vanilla and hdp as default plugins to make minimal
config easier.

Implements blueprint use-stevedore

Change-Id: I96700bf34417c9bcd24d4f60b2deaa88a8c7c2d9

* tools/integration.sh: We can't update the requirements repo until
integration.sh is working and for that we need to install d2to1 into the
mirror. Usually this would require a requirements repo change, but
chicken and egg. Force it in along with pip and setuptools instead. This
can be removed when d2to1 is added to the requirements repo.

Change-Id: Ia60c3b65d4dbc025aad5944420c40c2c3283117c
"}]
commit_message:
Force d2to1 into the integration test mirror.

* tools/integration.sh: We can't update the requirements repo until
integration.sh is working and for that we need to install d2to1 into the
mirror. Usually this would require a requirements repo change, but
chicken and egg. Force it in along with pip and setuptools instead. This
can be removed when d2to1 is added to the requirements repo.

Change-Id: Ia60c3b65d4dbc025aad5944420c40c2c3283117c

[{'created': '2013-12-05 21:12:06.000000000', 'message': 'Build mirror using proper requirements.

* tools/integration.sh: Use the --no-update flag to run-mirror to make
sure that the repo checked out by devstack-gate is the repo used to
build the mirror. Otherwise `git reset --hard remote/origin/master` is
used which we do not want.

Change-Id: Ia35fb3fd981880604ff6a5b85ad28ff44ab515e4
'}]
commit_message:
Build mirror using proper requirements.

* tools/integration.sh: Use the --no-update flag to run-mirror to make
sure that the repo checked out by devstack-gate is the repo used to
build the mirror. Otherwise `git reset --hard remote/origin/master` is
used which we do not want.

Change-Id: Ia35fb3fd981880604ff6a5b85ad28ff44ab515e4

'}]
commit_message:
Launch job on new cluster gives option to persist

Fixes: bug 1240928

The action of launching a job on a new cluster now gives the
user an option to have the cluster persist after the exit
of the job via a checkbox at the bottom of the cluster
creation form.

Change-Id: If8d53c3a06ee9cd9a642f2bc73ca310b4e21f159

commit_message:
Adding ability to download job binaries

There is now the ability to download job binaries both
from the job binaires table and from the job binaries
description page.

Closes-Bug: #1251288

commit_message:
Add power control to PXE driver

Necessary node power control added to PXE driver.
Power control code moved to separate module for
usage in manager and drivers. Reboot handling added
to power control code.

Partially implements: blueprint pxe-mount-and-dd
Change-Id: Ic13c046c621211d9c1533325812955233441d2da

commit_message:
Fix missing imports of _

A number of files used _() but didn't import it.  Add the missing
imports.

Note that tox.ini is updated as well to ensure that the hacking rule
about only importing modules is ignored for this case.  This avoids
having to add #noqa to every instance of this import.

Test coverage that hits these code paths is being added in another
review, where this originally came up:
Idd883fda93be4f7d28554c26902da0b9744f0bf1

Closes-bug: #1258254
Change-Id: I19b89be8864ce3a27fef48d5b00e44110fa65adf

commit_message:
Use password masking utility provided in Oslo

Implement the mask_password function provided in Oslo-incubator's
log.py. Instead of having a specific version in Nova different from
other projects that are essentially doing the same thing.

Change-Id: I7e04b7d31d4d6959b17b1da9654553042eec70f1
Closes-Bug: #1247217

It's not safe to do a partial sync of a file from Oslo.  This exact version of log.py was never tested there so it's not possible to say conclusively that it works (or that it doesn't, it just plain hasn't been unit tested in this state).

The only way to split this up would be to sync each individual change in Oslo over in chronological order, but since there still won't be tests in Nova I'm not sure that gains you much.  Basically all of this code has been reviewed and unit tested and this is just a copy paste, albeit using the update script to make sure import paths and such get fixed up.

I know this is not ideal, but that's why we're trying to get as much graduated from oslo-incubator as possible so we can limit this copying madness to the stuff that is legitimately in enough flux that it can't guarantee a stable API. :-)"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-11-19 00:44:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Sync log.py from Oslo-incubator

This change syncs log.py and it's dependencies from Oslo-incubator to
include the password sanitation fix that landed in Oslo with commit
76b0cd10c414ae71e6f041adb431460b3337c63d.

The following is a list of the change IDs that this
commit is bringing in from the last sync of Oslo-incubator with
respect to the files we are touching.

2b40a10 python3: Fix UserString import
c331e74 Enable multiple translation domains for gettextutils
89369c3 gettextutils: port to Python 3
6d49bca Translate all substitution elements of a Message object
3970d46 Fix typos in oslo
88db9c8 When translating if no locale is given use default locale
53ebd30 python3: use six.text_types for unicode()
25c5854 Adds admin_password as key to be sanitized when logging
2251cb5 Do not name variables as builtins
04c1b5a Type check for Message param to avoid AttributeError

Change-Id: Ie4d5929604e3fc057ea09edbbf3adf16f8839a4e
Partial-Bug: #1247217

commit_message:
Add a bug statistics tool.

This is a first draft at a timeseries generator to extract an overview
of bug activity in Launchpad. I'm entirely sure that this can be
improved, mainly I wanted it up before the Nova meeting.

Change-Id: I887db503b8a0ce274f3819d90877ef14f13cbeff

commit_message:
Log parsing errors from pystache as errors

Currently if an error is encountered in the template syntax one can only
see "could not render moustache template...". The error from pystache is
often quite helpful.

Change-Id: If79c3c07a5171d5ff58993066976f10cd9c2a1c7

commit_message:
Revert "Support building wheels (PEP-427)"

'universal=True' means app supports py2 and py3 which isn't supported by
climate at least due to the eventlet dependency, so, my bad, it should
be reverted atm. W/o 'universal=True' wheel bdist still could be built.

This reverts commit 415a66430b3c395c8f442d89f4d4ec6d48378276

Change-Id: I721dc951f17e58a2c2a6b619a605e4b7f503072a

Hi lifeless,

Thanks for your review. Regarding the improvements - my thoughts were that building exception trace into __str__ is not the best practice. But since we still sometimes have conductor trace in the message (if rpc exception + server debug True) this won't be too bad. Perfect implementation would be to have separate properties for each trace (1. Conductor trace, 2. API trace, 3. pythonclient trace) and do not touch __str__ at all, print all traces separately, but this doesn't lands smoothly to current code. We would need to cut out RPC traceback from message on server plus invent new 'debuginfo' to send it separately, OR we would need to cut it out on the client what is even worse.

Any thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-04 23:57:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Let CLI print exception traceback from 'debuginfo'

Response 'debuginfo' is used to carry server traceback in case of
error. If 'debuginfo' is not empty, append it to exception message,
so traceback will be printed together with message.

Change-Id: Id7900b64ec7fc9f906253ef0e2d754c2baa76067
Closes-Bug: #1255590

A few notes inline.

I think this is slightly different than what we want to do right now. 

I thought the plan was to do the following:

1) Change the schema so that task_info is separate, but keep the db_api interface the same (particularly in task_get_all) so that we don't have to change the domain
2) Change the task http api so that the serializer does not show task_info in list
3..N) Do all the other stuff we need to do to get tasks working properly
N + 1) Make domain and db_api changes so that we don't actually joinload the task_info

I think with some small modifications this patch could be a step in that direction. I know you care deeply about the performance of listing tasks. But I just want to make sure we are in a position where we can fix that performance issue nicely in the future.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2013-12-03 00:16:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 21.'}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2013-12-03 00:18:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

commit_message:
Introduce Task Info Table

- move 'input', 'message' and 'result' columns to table 'task_info'
- introduce migration script for the above db changes.
- appropriate tests are included

Co-authored-by: Nikhil Komawar <nikhil.komawar@rackspace.com>

partly implements bp async-glance-workers

Change-Id: I9867d609f4729572b72a44d1f05e353acf6c98d9

commit_message:
Add default arguments for Connection class

The fakelibvirt.Connection class, among other things, mocks
libvirt.virConnect which doesn't require any parameters. This is
causing a test to fail.

Change-Id: If77864cb0d0bd1dae20b490b8e87a32a0951b52e
Closes-Bug: 1257876

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-21 02:04:41.000000000', 'message': "Easy testing with alternate keystoneclient

It wasn't easy to test with an alternative keystoneclient, just
the checked out ones.

This change makes it easy to test with an alternative
keystoneclient, just set KSCTEST_REPO and alternatively
KSCTEST_BRANCH and run test_keystoneclient.KcOptTestCase.

Change-Id: I0af834d2861220b72b93265a1ddbfd8bc3d13d49
"}, {'created': '2013-11-24 20:21:23.000000000', 'message': "Easy testing with alternate keystoneclient

It wasn't easy to test with an alternative keystoneclient, just
the checked out ones.

This change makes it easy to test with an alternative local
keystoneclient, just set KSCTEST_PATH to the path:

 KSCTEST_PATH=/opt/stack/python-keystoneclient tox -e py27 KcOptTestCase

Change-Id: I0af834d2861220b72b93265a1ddbfd8bc3d13d49
"}]
commit_message:
Easy testing with alternate keystoneclient

It wasn't easy to test with an alternative keystoneclient, just
the checked out ones.

This change makes it easy to test with an alternative local
keystoneclient, just set KSCTEST_PATH to the path:

 KSCTEST_PATH=/opt/stack/python-keystoneclient tox -e py27 KcOptTestCase

Change-Id: I0af834d2861220b72b93265a1ddbfd8bc3d13d49

commit_message:
Import heartbeat_interval opt in API

The API for /v1/drivers needs to read the conductor.heartbeat_timeout
option from ironic.conductor.manager in order to get the list of
active conductor drivers from the database.

Change-Id: If6abd41ac01b3704bbdda0212d07abcaa0339ef9
Closes-bug: 1258207

commit_message:
Backport Havana: excercices: aggregates needs to be more flexible

The actual regex checks a result in python format and
because of the change in the bug 1132961, Jekins failed.

I have update the regex to work with the old result
and the new result.

    From: 75e851a

Change-Id: Idb23ddd32f7f7bf0eeecba9794c705365e3b2122
Closes-Bug: 1239726

commit_message:
Generate glance image with SCSI bus type for ppc arch

This patch fixes wrong assumptions for bus types of disk and cdrom
on ppc64. Qemu driver assumes IDE bus type for cdrom device, which
is not supported on ppc arch.
Adds capability to add --property key-value to the glance
image-create command.
Using double brackets for portability reasons.

Change-Id: I9f55fa0b6a894a93926e4f8c3d0ea410b5283f9c

commit_message:
Fix savanna-dashboard git repo clone dest

It breaks savanna d-g jobs due to the ERROR_ON_CLONE=True in d-g
(enforce that nothing will be cloned during the installation).

Change-Id: I0531e1baf7252c31eb63ee5b46c28d1dfa7d0a1b

commit_message:
Fix AttributeError(s) from get_v4/6_ips_by_interface

Add some defensive code to prevent AttributeError especially
when virtual_interface_get_by_uuid returns None. Add some basic
tests for good and bad data returned from
virtual_interface_get_by_uuid

Change-Id: I0ee1bb2087a6ed2619ac343534e4ade84e08d9bd
Closes-Bug: 1246087

I do like where this is going, but I have a couple of comments.

Firstly, i would like to something in the claims test method to test against these resources, just as there is for cpu, memory and disk. 

Scheduling is divided into three parts: the scheduler decides where to place an instance (which can now be based on this new information), the claims test method in compute determines if that decision can actually be supported by the target compute node, and lastly the resource consumption is updated in the resource tracker. You have enabled the scheduler to make decisions based on the new resources plugins, but you have not provided a way to test the decisions in the claims test. 

I think adding this claims test part would be a significant enhancement. It would bring the new resources into the proper scheduling cycle and allow plugins to be written that handle resource consumption.

But otherwise I think this is doing a good job and will be useful."}, {'account_id': 7641, 'date': '2013-07-19 08:53:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-19 09:52:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Works for me

commit_message:
Make compute support monitors and store metrics

According to the 'nova.conf', compute can call the
appropriate monitors and store metrics into compute nodes
as a json dictionary.

This is part of the blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling and
the blueprint generic-host-state-for-scheduler.

Change-Id: I2d9bde7ae838f2588c19874d87de6653859b3ac4

[{'created': '2013-10-17 08:26:19.000000000', 'message': 'Change conductor live migrate task to use select_destinations()

Live migration currently makes calls to scheduler select_hosts() to select
a suitable target host if none is given. Other tasks instead queries the
scheduler by making calls to select_destinations(). Since the latter call
basically returns the same result, and because live migration is the only
task using select_hosts(), changing to select_destionations() means the
scheduler would no longer need the select_hosts() call.

Change-Id: I984ccc2317184ba8f6b292c91717f52a81cf73d7

commit_message:
Change conductor live migrate task to use select_destinations()

Live migration currently makes calls to scheduler select_hosts() to select
a suitable target host if none is given. Other tasks instead queries the
scheduler by making calls to select_destinations(). Since the latter call
basically returns the same result, and because live migration is the only
task using select_hosts(), changing to select_destionations() means the
scheduler would no longer need the select_hosts() call.

Change-Id: I984ccc2317184ba8f6b292c91717f52a81cf73d7

@Russell Bryant
When a compute node is down, the instance in that host can not be synchronazied status, and its status was alway "active"or "shutoff", User doesn't know the compute service is down. If the user performe action such as "stop", there is no exception ,only instance's task_state changed for powering-off forever,
When the compute service is up again . we can't perform any actions for that instance due to its task_state  is powering-off. That's why I want to add precheck compute servie .
This issue can be reproduced easily. just stop compute service , then perfom action .

1)Yes, I think other actions will meet the same issue, I would like to add in other patches:), and adding precheck will take costs. Maybe we can put the check in compute/api.py

@Chris Behrens	
If the check in compute/api.py ,that will work for cell,right ?'}, {'account_id': 6722, 'date': '2013-09-25 08:14:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-25 08:45:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Doesn't seem to work

[{'created': '2013-09-22 09:07:04.000000000', 'message': "Add service precheck before stop/start instance

Current api doesn't have precheck for compute service's status before
stop/start instance, this lead to leave instance's task_state as
'powering-off'/'powering-on' forever. We can't stop/start the instance
even the compute service is available.

Fixes bug #1228804

Change-Id: I236a77a0cf5a8fd5e31bac708f0650df22e8f3eb
"}, {'created': '2013-09-22 10:02:28.000000000', 'message': "Add service precheck before stop/start instance

Current api doesn't have precheck for compute service's status before
stop/start instance, this lead to leave instance's task_state as
'powering-off'/'powering-on' forever. We can't stop/start the instance

if the compute service isn't avalible when stop/start instance.

commit_message:
Prevent stop/start instance when service is down

When compute service is down, Performing start/stop aciton will leave
instance's task_state as 'powering-off'/'powering-on' until the
compute service is available again. We need notify this issue to api
layer through raising exception. This patch add pre-check compute
service before performing action and prevent changing instance
task_state if compute service is down.

Closes-Bug: #1228804

Change-Id: I236a77a0cf5a8fd5e31bac708f0650df22e8f3eb

I'm not sure if this objection really belongs here but the service catalog is supposed to be guaranteed by the API.

I would like some information on how this is going to impact the service catalog. Taking an example if i have the "US" region with the subregions "EAST" and "WEST" with each subregion containing an image service.

From the client perspective if someone were to ask for a url for an image service in "US" then I would consider either of those in the subregion to be a valid response. How is this information going to be encoded so that the client knows the region hierarchy?'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2013-11-18 17:19:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

On 11/17/2013 11:25 PM, Jamie Lennox (Code Review) wrote:
> I would like some information on how this is going to impact the service catalog. Taking an example if i have the "US" region with the subregions "EAST" and "WEST" with each subregion containing an image service.

Yes. This is unfortunately a weakly-defined part of the Identity API. The service catalog itself should probably continue to act in the exact same manner as it does today: return the list of all endpoints and let the client filter for a particular endpoint based on the supplied --os-regionname CLI parameter.

>  From the client perspective if someone were to ask for a url for an image service in "US" then I would consider either of those in the subregion to be a valid response. How is this information going to be encoded so that the client knows the region hierarchy?

I don't think it needs to be encoded at all. Return all the endpoints in the service catalog (as is the case now) and let the client determine which one to pick. I believe the default behavior in the clients right now is to just pick the first endpoint of a particular service_type that matches the supplied --os-regionname.

A reworking of the service catalog API calls itself is outside (purposely) the scope of this particular patch, but I agree it should be addressed in the future.

Best,
-jay'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-11-19 01:47:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

So the service catalog is not currently layed out in the identity-api document. It really should be and at this point it needs to be considered stable to what the current code is. But to be clear the primary purpose of the service catalog and keystoneclient in general is not the CLI. Currently regions are badly handled, there are current open reviews that go part way to fixing this. 

My question relates essentially to "Return all the endpoints in the service catalog (as is the case now) and let the client determine which one to pick" - how? How from the information that is contained in the service catalog is the client supposed to know that "EAST" is a subregion of "US"? I don't want to have to query the server again about this.

I'm willing to accept that changes to the service catalog information may not belong in this review, but to my mind this is vital to actually making use of the nested regions and i want to make sure that there is a plan for how we deal with the SC.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-11-20 15:54:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Add proposed /regions resource to Keystone 3.2 API

This patch adds initial specification for the proposed
regions resource collection in the v3.2 Keystone API.

The regions resource allows for a deployer to describe
a hierarchical layout of their entire deployment, with
regions having an optional parent region.

partially implements bp first-class-regions

Change-Id: Ic49c0aeb2bec7327699d9c7e72df556d78b20e32

[{'created': '2013-12-03 23:41:05.000000000', 'message': "Update OSC's CommandManager subclass

cliff.commandmanager.CommandManager gained an option, update
openstackclient.common.commandmanager.ComamndManager to match.

Also add CommandManager.get_command_groups() to return a list of the
currently loaded command groups.  I expect this to be useful in
upcoming client diagnostic commands for plugins/extensions.

If these turn out to be generally useful we'll propose them to
upstream cliff.

Change-Id: Ic15a7ca0ef975ca679e753be861be7c628b8e10c
"}]
commit_message:
Update OSC's CommandManager subclass

cliff.commandmanager.CommandManager gained an option, update
openstackclient.common.commandmanager.ComamndManager to match.

Also add CommandManager.get_command_groups() to return a list of the
currently loaded command groups.  I expect this to be useful in
upcoming client diagnostic commands for plugins/extensions.

If these turn out to be generally useful we'll propose them to
upstream cliff.

Change-Id: Ic15a7ca0ef975ca679e753be861be7c628b8e10c

commit_message:
Use urlutils functions instead of urllib/urllib2

urllib and urllib2 were reorganized in Python 3. This patch cleans up
code where use urllib/urllib2 directly. Also add unquote_plus to
py3kcompat urlutils.

See http://docs.pythonsprints.com/python3_porting/py-porting.html#url-related-modules

Implements: blueprint make-python3-compatible
Change-Id: If1c4a4d0f0dcfd98d4091e2adc5762933677eb67

Merge common utils from Oslo-Incubator

Merge the comon modules first as a preparation
for the bigger submodule merges. This brings
in among other things a lot of Hacking related
code style fixes.

commit_message:
Add marconi support to devstack

Marconi has an optional dependency on keystone for authentication. This
code was tested with everything enabled and also with the following
localrc:

    STACK_USER=fedora
    SERVICE_TOKEN=secrete
    ADMIN_PASSWORD=secrete
    MYSQL_PASSWORD=secrete
    RABBIT_PASSWORD=secrete
    SERVICE_PASSWORD=secrete

    disable_all_services
    enable_service qpid
    enable_service key
    enable_service mysql
    enable_service marconi-server

Implements blueprint marconi-devstack-integration
Implements blueprint devstack-support

Change-Id: I13495bcc5c5eb66cee641894e9f84a0089460c8b

commit_message:
Ensure NVP API connection port is always an integer

Convert the 'port' part of a NVP endpoint to int before passing
it to the NVP API client.

Change-Id: I15137d943ab950cb5cc80d7af2971bce3ac1a265
Closes-Bug: #1255519

commit_message:
Add tests for testing swift slo middleware

Add test cases for Swift's Static Large Objects (SLO) feature which
supports management of a large object by using a manifest file.
Test cases contain functional tests for testing PUT, HEAD, GET
and DELETE.

Change-Id: I8cd1edb7290a76181303b1fd5b6738e9f1c157ff
Implements: blueprint test-swift-slo-middleware
Related-Bug: #1240856

commit_message:
VMware: fix disk extend bug when no space on datastore

In the event that thete is no space on the datastore then ensure
that the disk extension is cleaned up accordingly.

A number of files would be left behind on the datastore.

Change-Id: Ica9daf9151e4fb1874fa8b1d7247080860ef4ae2
Related-Bug: #1255355

commit_message:
Fix a minor error in method _get_alternative_flavor

Current ServerDiskConfigTestJSON._get_alternative_flavor
defined in file test_disk_config.py cannot get the correct
alternative_flavor. The condition used to decide whether
the flavor_alt should be used can never return true because
a integer never equals to a string.

Change-Id: Ib4f06d0a93580d84fcea0f475695f2c9fd34856b

commit_message:
Fixes how instances methods are not deregistered

It appears that instance methods do not get removed
due to not passing the 'is' check, so switch to using
a new reflection utility method which can handle this
equality check in a way that actually works.

Also adds tests to make sure this does not occur again.

Closes-Bug: 1257550

Change-Id: Iab47dd62cb61de0d93d0fe8d90e59772beebeaeb

commit_message:
Add heartbeat_interval to new 'conductor' cfg group

Add new 'conductor' config option group, to separate the various options
specific to this service which will be added in subsequent patches.

Add heartbeat_interval option to control how often a conductor updates
its status record in the database.

Fix a minor issue with the unit test associated with this method
and rename it to be more consistent with other unit test names.

Change-Id: I0ea71231ba7a6f20b94f4bca7de2a2f49bc4a428

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-04 21:57:48.000000000', 'message': "xenapi: Update VM memory overhead estimation

Update the VM memory overhead estimation formula to be more accurate
based on a more comprehensive survey of VM overhead values found in
the Rackspace public cloud's XenServer hosts.

The old formula was under-predicting overhead in some cases, especially
when VMs had a larger number of VCPUs.

Closes-Bug: 1257874

Change-Id: I338c72145fe41dae094516f7f832f15efc46a530
"}]
commit_message:
xenapi: Update VM memory overhead estimation

Update the VM memory overhead estimation formula to be more accurate
based on a more comprehensive survey of VM overhead values found in
the Rackspace public cloud's XenServer hosts.

The old formula was under-predicting overhead in some cases, especially
when VMs had a larger number of VCPUs.

Closes-Bug: 1257874

Change-Id: I338c72145fe41dae094516f7f832f15efc46a530

foreign_keys parameter of orm.relationship should point to local columns.
Currently for MeteringLabel it points to Router.tenant_id column which causes
routers tenant_id clearing on label deletion.

Closes-Bug: #1249188
Change-Id: Iccc0daf4f6edd537fd7f9e4b2fc4be094543ca5d
"}]
commit_message:
Fix MeteringLabel model to not clear router's tenant id on deletion

foreign_keys parameter of orm.relationship should point to local columns.
Currently for MeteringLabel it points to Router.tenant_id column which causes
routers tenant_id clearing on label deletion.

Closes-Bug: #1249188
Change-Id: Iccc0daf4f6edd537fd7f9e4b2fc4be094543ca5d

This needed for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/55978/

HEAT uses neutronclient and this client raises "NeutronClientException: Invalid input for floating_network_id. Reason:
'public' is not a valid UUID." when template contains network_id 'name' instead of UUID.

Also fixed typo in Floating IP label

'}]
commit_message:
Reverted floating-ip-pool UUID sending to Savanna

This needed for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/55978/

HEAT uses neutronclient and this client raises "NeutronClientException: Invalid input for floating_network_id. Reason:
'public' is not a valid UUID." when template contains network_id 'name' instead of UUID.

Also fixed typo in Floating IP label

Change-Id: I74c4e4d1f4498000fb4946239c8dbabf34b5bd6a

commit_message:
Don't run non-tests

Some functions in keystone.tests.core were running that were not
tests because the name contained "test".

Functions that are not tests should not be run as tests, so these
functions were renamed.

Change-Id: Icb0f0186b2b20e7b6e5a42e068fde2b89e771741

commit_message:
Replace node_id to node_uuid on Ports

The commit https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56682/ introduced node_uuid
for Ports in the Ironic API, this patch adjusts the client to reflect
that change.

Change-Id: Iae9ee8c5cadeae7803f74cca010bb6f8683667c0

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-19 06:24:51.000000000', 'message': "Improve unit test coverage for Cisco plugin nexus code

Closes-Bug: #1190622

This fix improves the unit test coverage for the Cisco Nexus plugin's
cisco_nexus_network_driver_v2.py and cisco_nexus_plugin_v2.py
source files from:
cisco_nexus_network_driver_v2: 72%
cisco_nexus_plugin_v2:         79%
To:
cisco_nexus_network_driver_v2: 99%

commit_message:
Improve unit test coverage for Cisco plugin nexus code

Closes-Bug: #1190622

This fix improves the unit test coverage for the Cisco Nexus plugin's
cisco_nexus_network_driver_v2.py and cisco_nexus_plugin_v2.py
source files from:
cisco_nexus_network_driver_v2: 72%
cisco_nexus_plugin_v2:         79%
To:
cisco_nexus_network_driver_v2: 99%
cisco_nexus_plugin_v2:         94%

Much of what the remaining "uncovered" code (coverage tool
reports as partially covered) can be attributed to the
coverage tool not being aware that execution does not
continue at the end of a save_and_reraise_exception()
context block (i.e. the exception will be reraised, but
the coverage tool isn't aware of this).

This fix and coverage results are dependent on the fix for #1246080.

Change-Id: Ie0e11fc0a12502739fb39bb4b30deb04dd31b7b0

commit_message:
Remove plugin from service/instances.py

The usage of plugin in savanna.service.instances:scale_cluster is improper.
The instances should work with infrastructure only and do not call plugin
methods.

That is the preliminary change before introducing Heat provisioning.

Implements blueprint infra-provisioning-extensions

Change-Id: I98ba640ae13bf2067c5e985c9009e21dd813b3f3

commit_message:
Fixed wrong flavor validation

* Nova has designed feature that deleted flavor could be shown by its id.
* Nova flavor list command doesn't show deleted flavors, so moved validation to check flavors in nova.flavors.list()
* Updated appropriate unit tests

commit_message:
Drop os.common.exceptions

The os.common.exceptions lib was deprecated in oslo and all usages should be
removed.

We're only using os.common.exceptions.Error:

class Error(Exception):
    def __init__(self, message=None):
            super(Error, self).__init__(message)

and we have our own base exception class with all needed stuff
savanna.utils.exceptions.SavannaException.

Change-Id: Ib4a1601e4b71bb38d293d457afaffa1c979b8ffb
Closes-Bug: #1208734

commit_message:
[vbox] Increasing memory/disk size in vbox scripts.

Closes-bug #1253097

When controller is deployed with Ceph,
768Mb of RAM is not enough. So we have
to increase the default amount of memory
required to run demo environment.
Also, as we now give more space on
controllers for root partition, increased
default disk size as well.

Change-Id: I791f26c94c54ce6be48116fc2eaa9e6464da5738

commit_message:
Midonet to support port association at floating IP creation

The Midonet plugin currently does not support associating floating IPs with
ports at floating IP creation time. This bug is created to add this support.

Change-Id: Ie57ebffa5185f26138c04b9836067417c6dc1388
Closes-Bug: #1249957

[{'created': '2013-12-04 21:46:12.000000000', 'message': "Call cfn-create-aws-symlinks in boothook.sh

Images which have heat-cfntools installed from rpm or deb
will not have cfn tool links in /opt/aws/bin.

This change runs cfn-create-aws-symlinks during cloud-init
boothook.sh. It should do the following:
* if no cfn tools exist in /opt/aws/bin, symlinks from /usr/bin
  will be created
* if cfn tools exist in /opt/aws/bin, no symlinks are created
* if cfn-create-aws-symlinks doesn't exist, there will be no effect

This is required to use a vanilla Fedora 20 cloud image with heat,
which has heat-cfntools pre-installed.

Change-Id: I5426fdad3031f91b4b9c1f9c9c19ac9cc42cf2dd
"}]
commit_message:
Call cfn-create-aws-symlinks in boothook.sh

Images which have heat-cfntools installed from rpm or deb
will not have cfn tool links in /opt/aws/bin.

This change runs cfn-create-aws-symlinks during cloud-init
boothook.sh. It should do the following:
* if no cfn tools exist in /opt/aws/bin, symlinks from /usr/bin
  will be created
* if cfn tools exist in /opt/aws/bin, no symlinks are created
* if cfn-create-aws-symlinks doesn't exist, there will be no effect

This is required to use a vanilla Fedora 20 cloud image with heat,
which has heat-cfntools pre-installed.

Change-Id: I5426fdad3031f91b4b9c1f9c9c19ac9cc42cf2dd

(2 inline comments)

Hi Ed,

Thanks for the updated patch.

Can you post some details on your testing? It would help me understand what you are seeing and how the patch addresses it.

What version of the api were you using? What backed store were you using? What size images were you using? How many concurrent threads were active? What were the results w.r.t scheduling fairness before and after this code change?

Were you using v2? If so could you switch to using v1 and retry the downloads which tee into cache (before and after applying the patch) and let me know how that behaves? I suspect that since the v1 downloads are already wrapped in a cooperative_reader the patch won't affect the results in that case, but it would be great to get the data. If wrapping the downloaded object (ie current v1 approach) works then rather than patching at the point where we tee into cache we should patch the v2 download iter in the same way as v1 -- which will work whether cache is enabled or not. Thanks!

Marking as '-1' mainly for the suspected duplicate wrapping in cooperative_iter in the v1 download case, and possibly to take the same approach for v2. (Based on more details of testing.)"}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-11-29 12:48:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: (2 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-11-29 13:16:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Stuart,

So, I performed a fairly crude test but it did clearly demonstrate that (a) the reads were not yielding on each chunk read and (b) adding in the read yield results in evenly balanced reads. Running the following script from a couple of client nodes with before and after code, you get to see the effect:

#!/bin/bash -eu
IMG_ID=$1
export OS_IMAGE_API_VERSION=1
# Do some concurrent downloads
for i in {0..8}
do
    echo $i
    glance image-download $IMG_ID > img.$i &
done
watch -n 0.5 ls -alF

What I see with the new code is that the downloads all happened at about the same rate. Without the patch they are fairly random. I ran this test with the V1 and V2 api. For V1 I see a significant improvement whereas V2 I only see a slight improvement. I also tested that neither api's were using cooperative iterators by adding a log to iterator and watching for it.

As you pointed out the cache tee is actually getting past a cooperative iter so I will remove the write mod."}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-11-29 13:22:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-11-29 13:25:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 6737, 'date': '2013-11-29 13:32:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-11-29 13:32:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Make image cache reads cooperative

The image cache now yields after each chunk read
which should provide a more balanced response
to concurrent download requests.

Closes-bug: 1247144
Co-authored-by: Hirofumi Ichihara <ichihara.hirofumi@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Change-Id: I509af8de107dc2859d2276a86e3779c3f9e761ac

"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-12-04 17:11:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

We decided that global registration, and the import time side effects, are an anti-pattern. When I return home, I will be working on the new config generator app using entry points from https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo/+spec/improve-config-discovery-for-docs"}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-12-05 10:15:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I agree that the global thing doesn't looks good.

But I have an other use case:

If the cfg.CONF is not registered globally, I cannot use cfg.CONF.import_opt() to declare the opt dependencies between modules.

Example: ceilometer needs to be sure that "notification_topics" opt is available and that opt come with oslo.messaging

cfg.CONF.import_opt() permit to be sure at module load that notification_topics will be available at runtime.

Currently with oslo.messaging, if I want to read the value of "notification_topics", I need be sure that it have created a "Transport" object before.

I think I can deal with that in ceilometer because for now we use only one Transport object loaded very soon in ceilometer.

So, I'm ok to abandon this patch, if you think the import_opt is not a issue.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-12-05 13:12:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Registers cfg options globally

This patch registers the cfg options globally

Without this the config file generator cannot discover oslo.messaging config
options.

Closes bug #1241566

Change-Id: Iabe5f6ac67c6edf244484938e7d7b958d133b93c

commit_message:
Renamed sample with OpenStack provider

The deployment samples are located at doc/samples/deployments after when
a patch with separation of samples was merged.

Also, this patch contains renaming of sample devstack-lxc to
devstack-in-lxc for the reason to explicitly indicate difference between
a deploy engine and a server provider.

blueprint rally-docs

Change-Id: I9672fc217d012a29fc58297e738cf65d6e52c8a9

commit_message:
Fix no busybox symlinks issue on rhel

busybox on rhel has no `--list' option, which cause populate_busybox
can not create busybox symlinks. So the ramdisk created will not work
totally.

Fixes bug #1257669

Change-Id: I4f905673bb577867c99e0ccc0756c56a292474f5

This sleep is a workaround to avoid the problem list_servers
cannot get servers in test_list_servers_by_changes_since.
If start_time and the server creations are the same timestamp
(by second unit) in setUpClass, Nova does not return the server
through list-servers API.
This sleep makes the timestamp difference between start_time and
the server creations by second unit.

Change-Id: Ida0bb74a8c50b798da2046cfac5239058bb7b090
Closes-Bug: #1236585
'}]
commit_message:
Add sleep(1) to avoid filtering out servers

This sleep is a workaround to avoid the problem list_servers
cannot get servers in test_list_servers_by_changes_since.
If start_time and the server creations are the same timestamp
(by second unit) in setUpClass, Nova does not return the server
through list-servers API.
This sleep makes the timestamp difference between start_time and
the server creations by second unit.

Change-Id: Ida0bb74a8c50b798da2046cfac5239058bb7b090
Closes-Bug: #1236585

[{'created': '2013-11-28 08:11:09.000000000', 'message': 'Do not create an unnecessary file "ml2"

Previously when running devstack with Neutron ML2 plugin,
an unnecessary file "ml2" is created in devstack directory.
It is because when the first argument is not defined the second
argument becomes the first one.

This change moves the first "options" argument of populate_ml2_config
to the last and checks the given options has a value before adding
them to a file.

Change-Id: I9ff40456798c42216d414d5f8d443e671ab7d497
Close-Bug: #1255853
'}]
commit_message:
Do not create an unnecessary file "ml2"

Previously when running devstack with Neutron ML2 plugin,
an unnecessary file "ml2" is created in devstack directory.
It is because when the first argument is not defined the second
argument becomes the first one.

This change moves the first "options" argument of populate_ml2_config
to the last and checks the given options has a value before adding
them to a file.

Change-Id: I9ff40456798c42216d414d5f8d443e671ab7d497
Close-Bug: #1255853

commit_message:
Add new stack phase: post-extra

The current existing phases "post-config" and "extra" are not
sufficient to allow local.conf overrides to extra type services
because they run after the services are installed and configured.
This commit introduces a new phase called "post-extra" that runs
after these existing phases. With this change, users are able to
leverage local.conf to provide overridden options to services
like Tempest.

Change-Id: I5d758eebfda804dd1d8cbc3d5cc35ef4dcc8c96f
Closes-Bug: #1249085

commit_message:
Add collection count to stack list

Add an optional parameter ``with_count`` to the stack_list API to
allow the inclusion of the collection count in the body of the response

When passing the parameter, the response looks like:
{
  'stacks': [...],
  'count': 42
}

blueprint: count-stacks
Change-Id: I560cfff9d327db9b325e7cf4786bd2fcd71d47b2

commit_message:
Moved quota headroom calculations into quota_reserve

Moved headroom calculations into quota_reserve and modified headroom
calculations to take into account -ve quota limits (unlimited) on
cores and ram.

Updated test cases to generate OverQuota exceptions with new headroom
parameter.

Added new tests for 'unlimited' quotas to test_quota.py in
 QuotaIntegrationTestCase and DbQuotaDriverTestCase classes.

Add Exception kwargs checking for OverQuota and QuotaError exceptions.

Change-Id: I855b0cad495182c5c4ee42b2acf5eedd198557b5
Closes-Bug: #1224453 min_count ignored for instance create
(cherry picked from commit 30fa37e7776831d6f8022f52d3d92f62189fb702)

commit_message:
Use @six.add_metaclass instead off __metaclass__

The __metaclass__ property cannot be used in python3.

Implements blueprint make-py3x-compatible

Change-Id: Iac828d0865549f0526a7ae2cd1b37895488684d6

I still have a few reservations here. Might be unrealistic, but I'd still like a mechanism for an operator to override/specify this value via configuration rather than code modification. That may not be completely counter to this implementation, but in the end I see this as an operator feature as well as a mechanism for Heat itself to convey resource plugin support."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-25 14:22:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Randall - I was thinking that we would have a decorator for things like deprecating classes, so we could do:

  @resource.deprecated
  class MyResourceType(resource.Resource):
      pass

but, more importantly, we could also do:

  def resource_mapping():
      return {'My::Resource::Type': resource.deprecated(MyResourceType)}

and since modules in the plugin directory can override built-in plugins, the operator would only need to provide a plugin module, the full contents of which could be something like e.g.:

  from heat.engine import resource
  from heat.engine.resources import instance

  def resource_mapping():
      return dict((n, resource.deprecated(cls)) for n, cls in instance.resource_mapping().items())

to ensure that all of the resource types exported in the heat.engine.resources.instance module were deprecated. Do you think that would satisfy your use-case? It's effectively a configuration file (i.e. no modification to upstream code is required) that happens to be written in Python.

This patch seems pretty heavyweight to me, but I can't think of a reason to reject it. No doubt we will eventually need most of that stuff (the version part seems suspect though)."}, {'account_id': 7331, 'date': '2013-11-27 08:34:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Zane, agree with you, we may add some decorators, which would change support status of resources. And it would use support_status attribute from this change.

 I can make it in a separate change request. Would it be a suitable solution?'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-27 13:10:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

[{'created': '2013-11-13 12:53:44.000000000', 'message': 'Add SupportStatus class for resources

SupportStatus class has following attributes:
- status (SUPPORTED, DEPRECATED, etc. All allowed support
statuses are defined)
- message (property for providing some information about status)
- version (when resource came into specific support status)

By default support status of each resource is SUPPORTED.

Support status added to Resource class as a static attribute.

Implements bp filter-resources-by-support

Change-Id: Ib3aacdb0f28b09ebeecfc3f13cf22587f8d57f03
'}, {'created': '2013-11-13 12:56:14.000000000', 'message': 'Add SupportStatus class for resources

SupportStatus class has following attributes:
- status (SUPPORTED, DEPRECATED, etc. All allowed support
statuses are defined)
- message (property for providing some information about status)
- version (when resource came into specific support status)

By default support status of each resource is SUPPORTED.

Support status added to Resource class as a static attribute.

commit_message:
Add SupportStatus class for resources

SupportStatus class has following attributes:
- status (SUPPORTED, DEPRECATED, etc. All allowed support
statuses are defined)
- message (property for providing some information about status)
- version (when resource came into specific support status)

By default support status of each resource is SUPPORTED.

Support status added to Resource class as a static attribute.

Implements bp resource-support-status

Change-Id: Ib3aacdb0f28b09ebeecfc3f13cf22587f8d57f03

Completed Nova-Network limitations checking in Nailgun. Tests added.

1) + VLANs of all networks shouldn't be intersected to each other (all network modes) or Fixed VLAN range (VLAN manager).
2) + IP address spaces of all networks in cluster shouldn't be intersected to each other (exception: Floating ranges can be in Public CIDR).
3) + IP address ranges inside Public and Floating networks shouldn't be intersected to each other.
4) + Public ranges should be in one CIDR which calculated by netmask.
5) + Public network should have a gateway field and it should belong to Public CIDR but should not be in any Public or Floating range.
6) + Public and Floating networks are rated as a single network when they assigned to nodes' physical interfaces. So they must share one VLAN and must be assigned together to one interface.
7) + Any physical interface of any node can have one assigned untagged network only (exception: point 6).
8) + All networks should belong to the allowed IP ranges (network of class A, B or C excluding loopback range).
9) + VLAN IDs shouldn't be out of range 2, 4094. Untagged network should have VLAN ID == None.
10)+ Number of Fixed networks should fit in Fixed CIDR and size of one Fixed network.
11)+ Every network group should have amount == 1 except Fixed network in case of VLAN manager.

Change-Id: Ifd5b26e4a167dcb8ec47537db1f9ea20a4ae09aa

2) + IP address spaces of all networks in cluster shouldn't be intersected to each other (exception: Floating ranges can be in Public CIDR).
3) + IP address ranges inside Public and Floating networks shouldn't be intersected to each other.

6) + Public and Floating networks are rated as a single network when they assigned to nodes' physical interfaces. So they must share one VLAN and must be assigned together to one interface.
7) + Any physical interface of any node can have one assigned untagged network only (exception: point 6).
8) + All networks should belong to the allowed IP ranges (network of class A, B or C excluding loopback range).
9) + VLAN IDs shouldn't be out of range 2, 4094. Untagged network should have VLAN ID == None.
10)+ Number of Fixed networks should fit in Fixed CIDR and size of one Fixed network.
11)+ Every network group should have amount == 1 except Fixed network in case of VLAN manager.

Change-Id: Ifd5b26e4a167dcb8ec47537db1f9ea20a4ae09aa
"}, {'created': '2013-12-04 16:20:39.000000000', 'message': "[PRD-2455] Complete nova-net limitations check

Completed Nova-Network limitations checking in Nailgun. Tests added.

1) + VLANs of all networks must not be intersected to each other (all network modes) or Fixed VLAN range (VLAN manager).
2) + IP address spaces of all networks in cluster must not be intersected to each other (exception: Floating ranges can be in Public CIDR).
3) + IP address ranges inside Public and Floating networks must not be intersected to each other.
4) + Public ranges and gateway must be in one CIDR which is calculated using netmask.
5) + Public network gateway field must not be in any of Public or Floating IP ranges.
6) + Public and Floating networks are rated as a single network when they assigned to nodes' physical interfaces. So they must share one VLAN and must be assigned together to one interface.
7) + Any physical interface of any node can have not more than one assigned untagged network (exception: point 6).
8) + VLAN IDs must be in range 2, 4094. Untagged network must have VLAN ID == None.
9) + Number of Fixed networks must fit in Fixed CIDR and size of one Fixed network.
10)+ Every network group must have amount == 1 except Fixed network in case of VLAN manager.

Both providers configuration restrictions:
1) + All networks must belong to the allowed IP ranges (network of class A, B or C excluding loopback range).
2) + Network address ranges and gateway must not intersect with subnetwork address and broadcast address.

Full description of network configuration limitations:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/limitations-of-networking-configuration

Change-Id: Ifd5b26e4a167dcb8ec47537db1f9ea20a4ae09aa
"}]
commit_message:
[PRD-2455] Complete nova-net limitations check

Completed Nova-Network limitations checking in Nailgun. Tests added.

1) + VLANs of all networks must not be intersected to each other (all network modes) or Fixed VLAN range (VLAN manager).
2) + IP address spaces of all networks in cluster must not be intersected to each other (exception: Floating ranges can be in Public CIDR).
3) + IP address ranges inside Public and Floating networks must not be intersected to each other.
4) + Public ranges and gateway must be in one CIDR which is calculated using netmask.
5) + Public network gateway field must not be in any of Public or Floating IP ranges.
6) + Public and Floating networks are rated as a single network when they assigned to nodes' physical interfaces. So they must share one VLAN and must be assigned together to one interface.
7) + Any physical interface of any node can have not more than one assigned untagged network (exception: point 6).
8) + VLAN IDs must be in range 2, 4094. Untagged network must have VLAN ID == None.
9) + Number of Fixed networks must fit in Fixed CIDR and size of one Fixed network.
10)+ Every network group must have amount == 1 except Fixed network in case of VLAN manager.

Both providers configuration restrictions:
1) + All networks must belong to the allowed IP ranges (network of class A, B or C excluding loopback range).
2) + Network address ranges and gateway must not intersect with subnetwork address and broadcast address.

Full description of network configuration limitations:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/limitations-of-networking-configuration

Change-Id: Ifd5b26e4a167dcb8ec47537db1f9ea20a4ae09aa

[{'created': '2013-11-22 10:20:11.000000000', 'message': "Fix OVS agent reclaims local VLAN

If a port disappears on an OVS agent, the port is removed of the lvm
vif_ports list. And if it's the last port of the network on this agent,
the network local VLAN is reclaim.

Change-Id: I07e03107eb86a84eeb8e4d06f27a1d2fbd7cea57
Closes-Bug: #1252284
(cherry picked from commit a5d996e381bd342f0204fcd99e8548cf28b20e92)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix OVS agent reclaims local VLAN

If a port disappears on an OVS agent, the port is removed of the lvm
vif_ports list. And if it's the last port of the network on this agent,
the network local VLAN is reclaim.

Change-Id: I07e03107eb86a84eeb8e4d06f27a1d2fbd7cea57
Closes-Bug: #1252284
(cherry picked from commit a5d996e381bd342f0204fcd99e8548cf28b20e92)

commit_message:
Fix bad call in port_update in linuxbridge agent

A call to update_device_down() was made on the wrong object.
Also adds unit tests for code paths to update_device_down() and
update_device_up().

Partial-Bug: 1256950
Change-Id: I34e364d4c29441d0b62b665a4ce1d02b5d08d465

commit_message:
Improve unit test coverage for Cisco plugin base code

Closes-Bug: #1190621

This fix improves test code coverage for the file:
neutron/plugins/cisco/network_plugin.py
from 34% to 98%.

Some of the changes made to realize this code coverage improvements
are the following:
- Core API methods (create_network, update_network, etc.) have been
  removed from the core plugin (network_plugin.py). These methods
  are currently unused. Before this change, we relied on the underlying
  model layer to inform the core plugin whether or not the model layer
  was capable of handling these core API calls itself via a 'MANAGE_STATE'
  attribute. However, there is only one existing model layer
  implementation (i.e. for Nexus plugin; the N1KV plugin does not use
  network_plugin.py), and that model layer supports the core API calls.
  Given that it is unlikely that another model layer for the Cisco Nexus
  plugin will ever be developed (esp. with the availability of the ML2
  plugin), so it makes more sense to delete this untested code.
- Exception raising for non-existent credentials has been removed from
  get_credential_details and rename_credential methods since
  exceptions are already raised for this condition in lower-level
  credential database code.
- The schedule_host, associate_port, and detach_port methods are
  deleted because these essentially do nothing useful (log a debug
  message and then return None), since these methods look for
  the same-named methods in the model layer, but these methods are
  not defined in the model layer.
- The helper functions _invoke_device_plugins and _func_name are
  deleted because they are no longer used.
- In unit test code for the Cisco QoS and credentials database, calls
  are now made indirectly through the core plugin (network_plugin.py)
  extension API methods, as a quick-and-easy way to provide code
  coverage for these core plugin methods.

Change-Id: I0c0d9e2b251a7c0355d83e495912302c5cc4d032

commit_message:
Fix metering iptables driver doesn't read root_helper param

With this patch the iptables driver instantiates the
iptables_manager with the correct root_helper value.

Change-Id: I9a37bae92dc12a8a78ea2d1b9fc5e995321ca322
Closes-bug: #1256036

commit_message:
Implement sync_power_state periodic task

Implement a periodic task in the ConductorManager which will check all
the existing, non-locked nodes and verify that their current power
states correspond to state stored in DB. If they differ, for now, log a
warning and update the DB using current power state.

This is a step towards keeping powered-off-nodes off.

Also, this removes the unused db.api.get_nodes method
and adds a new get_nodeinfo_list method.

Change-Id: I609fdbd7db6620de617b44f83c7ec35350f9178c
Blueprint: keep-powered-off-nodes-off

commit_message:
Remove used_limits extension from the V3 API

Remove the used_limits extension from the V3 API because
it shows usage for limits which are no longer going to be displayed
by the limits extension. See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/39872/
The limits are not being displayed there because they are already
available through the quotas extension.

Although the quotas extension currently only displays the quota limit
and not usage, the following proposed changeset adds display
of usage: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/32303/. And this is done
in a way which is much more consistent in terms of naming and interface
than used_limits does.

So we no longer need the used_limits extension

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I8ec1f300335ca4fc3b86323cc3af6bc1591da7bb

commit_message:
Fix unit tests when running in a virtualenv environment

When running the unit tests in a virtualenv we don't have access
to a real libvirt at the moment. The fake libvirt used for
testing has a different api for virConnect object. Update the test
to not use this class as a return value and instead just mock return
a dummy connection object.

This issue was introduced in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/57000/

Closes-Bug: 1257813

Change-Id: If082cdd458d5f3409ed7ecb99f712657727ec32d
