'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-12-02 10:55:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Given I3a65d5bc0e4469a071db9ac23ebc82196a3f3feb , I'd prefer to use an environment variable rather than a $(pwd)/root-passwd file

Do we have any other examples of doing something similar in di-b ? ISTM we use env vars or command line arguments for all similar parameters ?"}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-12-02 13:18:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with Mark, I'd like to see this as an environment variable.  I think that's  more consistent with how options that are specific to only one element are handled in other parts of diskimage-builder."}, {'account_id': 1726, 'date': '2013-12-02 15:29:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

From the description, the purpose of this element is to assists in debugging images, so storing it in a file, although insecure, is something needed in some cases: If you CD a testing env. you need to root passwd to access the image. It could be always the same (so an env variable is more than ok), or, ideally, could be random, in which case, it should be stored someplace just in case.

Maybe, the element could check for a env variable for the root passwd, and if not present, generate one randomly and store it someplace."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-03 05:23:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

So that patch should be reverted - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59621/ put up (and ugh, gerrit didn't wrap the entered message in the UI; will put it down and do that shortly.

We use environment variables badly, and I want us to stop using them as a UI; it's expedience, not intent."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-03 05:24:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

That said, there already is the stackuser element, so having a root password setting one is strictly redundant, perhaps we should just -2 this?'}, {'account_id': 7761, 'date': '2013-12-03 06:05:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Agree'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-12-03 06:33:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Yeah, I think it's best to push back on people using root and suggest the use of stackuser instead"}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2013-12-05 08:52:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Should this be abandoned then?'}, {'account_id': 7761, 'date': '2013-12-05 09:39:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Abandoned

use stackuser instead'}]

commit_message:
Add an element to change root password

Change root password to the content of file `root-passwd' under
current working directory.

Change-Id: I1d3d63856e1e46b5e07fef2df07c1d739cb5d318

commit_message:
Ensure context type is handled when using to_dict

Handle the case where the context passed into def pack_context() is a
dictionary. If a dictionary is passed in, we don't need to call to_dict
before updating the msg.

Closes-Bug: #1208971
Change-Id: I2ce0b28f97634e717868e0ee5525189338d4981c

commit_message:
Add internal testing for the stress test framework

This adds a unit test for StressAction class and a end2end test
case for the whole stress test framework.

Change-Id: I4d30a131c75736fa05ba63f71cd731374f7fb9ba

'}, {'created': '2013-12-02 23:04:26.000000000', 'message': 'Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Closes-bug: #1251757
Change-Id: I6051fb503663bb8c7c5468db6bcde10f6cf1b318
'}]
commit_message:
Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Closes-bug: #1251757
Change-Id: I6051fb503663bb8c7c5468db6bcde10f6cf1b318

commit_message:
Handle exceptions on create_dhcp_port

If a network/subnet is deleted while creating the dhcp
port, the agent will detect a conflict on state of the
network and deal with it accordingly.

A concurrent delete may manifest itself via a number
of exceptions, IPAddressGenerationFailure amongst others,
hence the refactoring of the error handling logic into its
own utility method.

Partial-bug: #1253344
Related-bug: #1243726

Change-Id: I442beb5f82f3db8786eea53926903ef0ba0efbf1

commit_message:
NetApp fix for vsadmin role failure for ssc

The ssc feature does not work with vserver admin
role. If the user is a vsadmin then he does cannot
use the ssc feature fully. This fix checks the access
and issues apis appropriately and also handles error
conditions.

Closes-Bug: #1253657

Change-Id: Ibc4409e5d5e6e36bba41e5f59dd94c05b87b1cde

Update hacking to hacking>=0.8.0,<0.9

print "" -> print("")
self.assertEquals -> self.assertEqual
self.assertNotEquals -> self.assertNotEqual

commit_message:
Use pipe between ceph backup diff export/import

We now use a piped transfer between the rbd export-diff
and import-diff for incremental backups/restores as
opposed to holding the entire diff in memory.

Change-Id: I33476d9b3934781413af5cd2867a11d825a5d78e
Fixes: bug 1244464
(cherry picked from commit d384d28e1c2c7c3ce0bd676fb1c2bdb8a2d98a03)

commit_message:
Add documentation for some API parameters

Add documentation for some parameters which can
be present in glance-api.conf:

* use_user_token
* admin_user
* admin_password
* admin_tenant_name
* auth_url
* auth_region
* auth_strategy

Fix for bug 1256952.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia5b731cabaec961f3a4226d30abd3bca9bd87651

commit_message:
Fixed Murano Platform tests

Added skip actions for all platform tests when
Open Stack does not meet to the Murano requirements.
This fix allows to resolve all false-negative tests results.

Change-Id: Id4e957d95e53c05a11ccdea388dac05f0a500f3c

commit_message:
Create memcache_servers option

Permits use of one or more memcache servers for token storage.
Use to override default server (localhost:11211) when token_driver
is keystone.token.backends.memcache.Token.

Change-Id: Iaeb0c896d4907fd520db9b60e3af002b3711bc75

[{'created': '2013-12-04 11:37:38.000000000', 'message': 'Closes-Bug: #1252005
Every field which is mandatory must be marked with an asterisk.But in the launch instance workflow,two fields "groups","network" are mandatory and not marked with asterisk.
The solution is every field which is mandatory or not must be in "contributes" in the respective workflow.And the Selected Networks uses a separate template _update_networks.html
So It can be hardcoded in the respective html page.

Change-Id: I0f6b372996b56ea79e7faa4ee8f84330cd1c30f0
'}, {'created': '2013-12-04 12:18:30.000000000', 'message': 'Missing asterisk in Launch Instance

Asterisk is missing for mandatory fields in security and networking tabs.

Every field which is mandatory or not must be in "contributes".

For Selected Networks field,asterisk can be added in _update_networks.html.

Closes-Bug: #1252005
Change-Id: I0f6b372996b56ea79e7faa4ee8f84330cd1c30f0
'}]
commit_message:
Missing asterisk in Launch Instance

Asterisk is missing for mandatory fields in security and networking tabs.

Every field which is mandatory or not must be in "contributes".

For Selected Networks field,asterisk can be added in _update_networks.html.

Closes-Bug: #1252005
Change-Id: I0f6b372996b56ea79e7faa4ee8f84330cd1c30f0

commit_message:
ComputeFilter shouldn't generate a warning for disabled hosts

Disabling a service is a normal operation, so this state should
not be included in the same log statement as a host that fails
the service_is_up() check.

A service which is enabled but not up deserved a warning rather
than debug entry.

By separating out the checks we also avoid the service check on
disabled hosts.

Change-Id: I1a398bc033ebe71f42ac117af7dae39502aceede
Closes-Bug: 1254356

commit_message:
Add back --token-only for invocation compatibility

This unused option should remain so that scripts that
use it do not break. It is suppressed so it will not
appear in the help.

Closes-Bug:1250731

Change-Id: I1180d8797d1e4c79dba92952931311cce50a1d3f

commit_message:
Add --include-pass option for grizzly backwards compat

Set X-Auth-User, X-Auth-Key on all stack commands to allow the
latest python-heatclient to work on grizzly heat.

Partial-Bug:1250731

Change-Id: I29d4785cf3520e809252b5aeab25cf471a88cde8

commit_message:
Set upload_image policy to control data upload

There was no policy to control data upload.
Up until today, the add_image policy was a all or nothing, from metadata
to the actual data. Now, with the combination of add_image and upload_image
an administrator will have finer control over the whole chain.

Change-Id: I1a7966ffb5c63dd8239a54fe2963b031d9fe1f9a
Closes-bug: #1254521

commit_message:
Port test_flavors into v3 part 2

This change set ports test_flavors into v3,
modifies necessary files like base, clients
to access the v3 api.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: Ia5dd4dbbb627394db4432dfb52f3b122b41ac8f2

Port test_flavors to v3 part 1

commit_message:
Fix neutron port-create --no-security-groups

Previously, this would pass in {'security_groups': null} to neutron-server
which uses is_attr() in _ensure_default_security_group_on_port() which returns
False as is_attr() now checks for None and not just ATTR_NOT_SPECIFIED.

Change-Id: I033ce62dbb91597541a8c7f773b9819d69761860
Closes-bug: 1257473

commit_message:
Ensure the sample policy file won't diverge

Currently rules should appear in both policy.v3cloudsample.json and
policy.json. In the future there may be a few exceptions that can be
documented by making the exception explicit in the test.

Change-Id: I3e9cdf64998d667941c44dc6edb48c2f7a9d37c4
Closes-Bug: #1255564

commit_message:
Added documentation to keystone.common.dependency.

All public attributes now have docstrings describing their interface,
and the module has a top level docstring as well. Previously,
documentation was very sparse.

Closes-Bug: #1252428
Change-Id: I9c83883a6d9ae3201c9037c979689cb82c232120

commit_message:
There is no need to set VM status to ERROR on a failed migration

VM state should not be set to ERROR, when the
migration failed beauce libvirt is unavailble on the destination.

Fixes bug #1233184
Change-Id: I36e4ed3842d7e33c1082ec95f860629eee23224e

commit_message:
Rip out the tempest coverage runs from devstack-gate

The coverage extension has been removed from nova so there is no
reason to keep the devstack-gate support around.

Change-Id: Ic580c0523eff64d7f00d16da0f04c1616e30b9c8

commit_message:
Bump hacking to 0.8

hacking 0.8 brings us bunch of python 3 compat rules.
Fix the python 3 compat issues to make this landable.

Change-Id: I0fbefefce92b506146e2bb833ffb0bd984b1c097
Partial-Bug: #1257301

commit_message:
Implement testing of migrations from oslo

Dependences: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/42307/ (should be reviewed).

This patch adds opportunity of migrations testing.
By this test each migration checks on mysql/postgres dialects in
upgrade > downgrade> upgrade mode.
Also models are tested to equality with actual database state.

Models will be tested on different things:
- columns (type, length, nullable),
- constraints (indexes, unique keys, foreign keys),
- list of tables.

bp: db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: I0c83d5988614689dceb1fb5d2ae356ac8c3964fc

commit_message:
Fix total vcpu calculation in libvirt driver

The get_vcpu_total method in libvirt driver currently returns the total
pcpu. This is not consistent with the get_vcpu_used method, which might
return a greater vcpu_used than vcpu_total. This fix uses
cpu_allocation_ratio parameter to calculate correct vcpu_total. Also
provide a test case to validate the data being returned.

More work is needed to return the pcpu.

Change-Id: I8ba648a2c3068fb906f609eaa6f064ada0fc4b38
Partial-Bug: #1202965

commit_message:
Instance.update messages sometimes have the wrong state values.

Compute instance.update messages that are not triggered by a state
change (e.g. setting the host in the resource tracker) have a
default (None) values for task_state, old_vm_state and old_ task_state.

This can make the instance state sequence look wrong to anything
consuming the messages (e.g Ceilometer, stacktach)

This change makes sure that the old and new vm_state and
task_state are always included in the message

fixes bug 1204169

Change-Id: Id6b87116f90af20db2d9ce9345e04f4cfb18bd78

Author: [Shixiong Shang, Randy Tuttle]
Date: Nov. 24, 2013

This commit enables Neutron with IPv6 SLAAC.

It introduces the fixes to the following problems:
1. IPv6 RA is not sent to IPv6 enabled internal tenant network
2. dnsmasq is bound to the interface other than the default
   gateway of tenant network
3. IPv6 address assigned to VM by OpenStack is not based on SLAAC standard
4. Neighbor Discovery packet is dropped by ip6tables filter rules
5. NAT and GARP are turned on for IPv6 subnets, which is not
   desirable.

The fixes are included in the following 4 files:
1. neutron.db.db_base_plugin_v2.py
2. neutron.agent.l3_agent.py
3. neutron.agent.linux.dhcp.py
4. neutron.agent.linux.iptables_firewall.py

Closes-Bug: #1242933
Closes-Bug: #1252852
Related Subteam: Neutron-IPv6-Subteam
Related BP: IPv6 Feature Parity

Change-Id: Ieb9b76fa106a9228d9d68e25e8d5c0152336d9b7

commit_message:
Adds IPv6 SLAAC Support to Neutron

Author: [Shixiong Shang, Randy Tuttle]
Date: Nov. 24, 2013

This commit enables Neutron with IPv6 SLAAC.

It introduces the fixes to the following problems:
1. IPv6 RA is not sent to IPv6 enabled internal tenant network
2. dnsmasq is bound to the interface other than the default
   gateway of tenant network
3. IPv6 address assigned to VM by OpenStack is not based on SLAAC standard
4. Neighbor Discovery packet is dropped by ip6tables filter rules
5. NAT and GARP are turned on for IPv6 subnets, which is not
   desirable.

[Patch1] Incorporated all comments in db_base_plugin_v2.py

Closes-Bug: #1242933
Closes-Bug: #1252852
Related Subteam: Neutron-IPv6-Subteam
Related BP: IPv6 Feature Parity

Change-Id: Ieb9b76fa106a9228d9d68e25e8d5c0152336d9b7

commit_message:
Sync common.db.sqlalchemy changes from olso

Sync changes to common.db.sqlalchemy
- two new common.db.exception classes
- new global locking of db tests, handled by lockutils
- db.sqlalchemy.test_migrations is included in Oslo now, so our
  tests are refactored to use that
- bump sqlalchemy-migrate requirement to 0.8.2

Also, remove the sqla-migrate 0.7.3 patching from
openstack/common/db/sqlalchemy/migration.py, as done in
change I646a5a8f427095e20b09fbf2db796d2644def6fc, to avoid
conflicts with >=0.8.x versions.

Change-Id: I23963e3e195516ffcb26bec95e45d111ab105345

subject: Changes hot.py to reserve the template keyword heat_template_metadata

'}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-14 20:59:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

RandallBurt: Noted on the HOT documentation. We are really looking for strong opinions on the name of the template section at the moment. Otherwise, stack_metadata wins by default :)'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-11-15 07:40:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with Randall that if top-level sections are introduced, this should be documented in the HOT template guide and spec, also how you prose this section to be used. I think such documentation in a patch would be good place for reviewers to share opinions.

As for the name 'stack_metadata': is it really stack metadata (stack being an instance), or rather template metadata? The BP reads more like this being template metadata."}, {'account_id': 6434, 'date': '2013-11-15 17:10:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Thomas, it could be both, stack and template metadata.  What name would you suggest?  Just "metadata"?  Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-15 17:16:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thomas/Keith, whether we call it "stack" or "template" seems like just semantics. Once the template is instantiated as a stack, the concept of the template being different from the stack doesn't really exist anymore. At least that is my impression. For that reason I could see it going either way but "stack" is the permanent form that the template takes and the display hints/metadata that are going to be defined in this section are just as relevant to the stack as they were to the template.

I'm working on the hot specification so once I get that patch up hopefully some of the use-cases are more apparent.'}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-15 22:07:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

For reference, here is the dependent review with the updated HOT specification. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56703/'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-11-15 23:01:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

stack_metadata is a bad name.  A stack is the instantiated version of template.  How about just plain ol' metadata, or if you want more verbosity try template_metadata."}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-15 23:25:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I actually like just calling it "metadata", that sounds excellent to me. :)'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-11-17 17:49:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Keith, Tim, from your further explanations I think I would prefer just 'metadata' - including 'stack' or 'template' in the name could just be confusing when some contained piece of data isn't really related to the thing (template or stack) the user is looking at at a given point in time."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-18 09:59:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I also wonder about the "stack_metadata" naming, but re just "metadata" we already have multiple usages of "metadata" terminology, and it is a very generic term so it could potentially be confusing.

Maybe "tags" might be more appropriate, which takes an arbitrary number of key/value pairs (value could be a json blob):
  heat_template_version: 2013-05-23
  description: My Wordpress Template
  tags:
    type: wordpress
    author: shardy
  ...'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-11-19 00:31:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

tags doesn't really match the use case if complex data structures are going to be stored within it.

It is metadata associated with the stack. I would imagine real-world usage would involve stack updates where the only change in the template is in the stack_metadata, and it is metadata related to actual stack resources.

My vote is for stack_metadata"}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-19 15:51:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I agree, "tags" indicates a simpler data structure than what will exist. I would prefer stack_metadata or template_metadata. metadata by itself would probably be confusing because of how overloaded it is.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-21 15:04:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> tags doesn't really match the use case if complex data structures are going to be stored within it.

Well like I said, the tag value would just be a string, which could contain anything you want, complex or not (json string containing a "complex" data structure, whatever)

I'm not really sure I understand the use-case related to "complex data structures", the bp seems to describe something pretty well aligned with the usage implied by "tags", is there some more complex use case which has been discussed?

I'm not even sure, if Heat is supposed to ignore it, why we need this data to be inside the Heat template - Swift already provided the capability to store arbitrary object metadata, as does git to some extent via git notes - implementing a template repository backed by one of those seems most likely so I'm not sure what we really gain by having this in the template.

Another crazy idea would be for Heat to optionally look for a "template" key in the parsed template tree, and if found, treat the data under that as the template.  Then folks could put absolutely whatever they like into their templates outside of that key and we wouldn't have to care about it at all.'}, {'account_id': 7714, 'date': '2013-11-21 20:27:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This keyword will contain complex json data structures which are not typically associated with "tags". See review https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56703/ for examples added to the HOT specification.

Even if we stored this data in Swift we would still need a way in the template to determine which version of the template is being used so that we can pull the appropriate information out of Swift. Right now there is no reserved place to put this kind of metadata in the template. If this data is stored directly in the template it will persist in the Stack, effectively and simply maintaining the correct values at the time of stack instantiation, as opposed to having to use a version number to go and look up these values out of a separate maintained repository (and still requiring a metadata reserved word for template version).

We could force Heat to only look for "template" for the actual template but I don't see how that accomplishes anything differently than doing the opposite and just reserving a keyword for "other" data.'}, {'account_id': 6434, 'date': '2013-11-22 20:43:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-11-22 20:43:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 7896, 'date': '2013-11-22 22:08:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This patch is consistent with the template documentation changes, so its good from that perspective, but given that this has attracted more discussions around naming and use of this attribute, I'm adding a comment with some observations I have about it.

When I look at this new attribute, it seems to me that is just a generic extension mechanism which is meant to be interpreted by specific tools, so why not name this "extensions", and have a "sub" attribute "name:" which hints as to what is the purpose of the data or who is the intended consumer of these values? Is possible I did not interpret this correctly, but this is how I read into it. The current template contents are meant to be interpreted and processed by the Heat engine, where as the data you intend to put in this new section is not (from my understanding), and therefore maybe we can call it an "extension"? as in beyond the "normal" template contents? I can see where this concept of extensions can be leveraged in different contexts (e.g. store layout of resources in a graphical rendering tool, store revision and/or history information, etc), and each of these "contexts" would be named in the extensions section.

Example:
extensions: 
  layout: 
    web_server: 
      h: 30
      w: 50
      x: 512
      ? "y"
      : 580
  revisions: 
    ? "1.1"
    : 
      description: "Good stuff"
      rev: 1
      ver: 1
    ? "1.2"
    : 
      description: "Even better stuff"
      rev: 2
      ver: 1

The the template file could get really big and obfuscated with this kind of information, so it would be nice if the "extensions" could handle references to external URL (file, http, etc) content, therefore supporting inline and by-reference values.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-11-22 22:53:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

only +1 to allow other heat-core to review.  My take on the blueprint is it makes sense to allow template developers to stuff things into the template that third party tools may use, but Heat would never use.

Since it isn't stack related but instead used for template developers to jam info into the dsl for third party tools, I like the naming of template_metadata as opposed to stack_metadata.

I generally dislike the idea of mixing json with yaml, so would prefer the info stay contained in yaml.

The need for tags seems overkill - yaml can handle nesting of data and is designed with that purpose in mind.

I don't like the idea of pulling data in from third party URIs as part of the template.  It seems like keeping the template and URI dependencies synchronized would be difficult, especially in a stack update scenario."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-11-22 22:58:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

After re-reading Edmund's concerns, a possible name could be extension_metadata - which would extract it from the overloaded terms of template and stack :)"}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-11-22 23:17:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Edmond, all good points, but I'd be loath to continue debating the name of the tag. Also, while I think its good to sub-divide the contents into audience-specific sub-sections, I also think that that's better served as a best-practice rather than something we should enforce with schema. After all, this is for the template author to use as-needed depending on what tools she is using and what sort of interoperability is desired. I think we keep that flexible and let those external tools define the things they are looking for. If they're smart, they'll namespace their data or recommend a known section."}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-11-25 08:50:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-25 09:37:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@Steve Dake:
> The need for tags seems overkill - yaml can handle nesting of data and is designed with that purpose in mind.

Different kind of tag IMO, yaml tags are about typing keys containing serialized objects, or using references to reduce duplication inside the template.

Also, most of this functionality is disabled when you use safe_load (as Heat does), so we cannot parse templates using advanced yaml functionality not supported by safe_load.  IMO we should not be encouraging folks to rely on such features, in fact we probably need to explicitly document that it is not supported.

All of this comes back to my main concern - if this data is not ever going to be used by heat, why should it be in a Heat template?

There is nothing to stop proprietary UI's (which appears to be the use-case for this, right?) storing template data inside data structures which contain other stuff related to the applications usage of those templates.  Since heat doesn't care about that other non-template data, neither should the template, it's application specific stuff, layered on top of Heat, so should be out-of-scope for HOT, IMHO."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-25 11:14:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

-1 to anything with 'metadata' in the name.

Seriously, just say no. We already have two completely different meanings of 'metadata' in Heat and it's confusing as hell. Don't add a third. Just imagine trying to explain to a user that no, the metadata you assign to a facade resource doesn't actually end up in the heat_template_metadata section of the provider template, you get it using {Fn::ResourceFacade: Metadata}, and actually these concepts aren't related at all and, by the way, neither of them ends up passing metadata to your Nova server.

Secondly, the blueprint for this is almost entirely content-free and doesn't provide any justification for needing a mechanism beyond YAML comments. (Yes! YAML allows comments!) I assume that such a justification exists, so please document it in the blueprint so that we can evaluate the suitability of this solution.

Open Source is a design methodology, it's not just about sharing code. The reason you're getting so much more push-back than you expected on some of these features is that the community is not involved in the design, just presented the solution as a Good Thing in and of itself, independent of any effects it may have. (The "Locked Outputs" thread on the ML is a canonical example of this mismatch of expectations playing out - there are 10 messages before we even discover the problem for which locked outputs is a [transparently terrible] solution.) Whatever internal design process is generating these solutions needs to happen in the OpenStack community IMHO.

(BTW in most OpenStack programs -1 is reserved for trivial typos in the commit message and a review like this would be an automatic -2. We try to be a bit friendlier around here, but hopefully not at the cost of clearly communicating our expectations around open design.)'}, {'account_id': 7585, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:44:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Looking at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56703/7 (there are wrong dependencies btw.)

I don't think this belongs to heat template itself. The template should not be polluted by metadata it is not using.

If we want to have and we need metadata for templates (there should be some use cases for that shown), it would be cleaner to track it in some separate service. Something like Glance for Heat. So something like this https://blueprints.launchpad.net/heat/+spec/heat-template-repo . But that is only if we need it.

Or what should be the advantage of having this right in the template? 

Also if this should have some UI use, it would be good to start conversation on Horizon list."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-11-27 23:22:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

It looks like we're going to make structured changes to the hot schema to support specific use cases."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-05 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-05 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-08-29 18:15:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Is there any reason not to pick a version and require that specific one?

That way, if a new hacking gets released and has a bug or defines a new check or something, then we don't immediately get failing tests.

We had that happen with pep8; version 1.3 came out, and suddenly Jenkins hated us because pep8 v1.3 defined new checks that Swift didn't pass. No code could merge until we either made hundreds of nitpicky whitespace changes or locked pep8 to an older version (and we chose the version lock)."}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-08-29 19:50:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

We can not freely pick versions, it needs to match exactly those in openstack/requirements.

If you check closely, this goes into the right direction of allowing a newer version, but not yet requiring it. Once all issues are fixed, requiring a new version can be done as a followup.

It does not allow arbitrary new versions, and hacking has a strict versioning policy. There won't be new checks in micro releases, and we disallow a newer minor release sneaking in."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-08-30 21:42:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

What happens in the gate jobs? AFAIK, they install things fresh each time, so right now Swift gets hacking 0.5.<latest>, whereas with this change Swift will get hacking 0.7.<latest>. Does that change introduce new checks that will break the gate jobs?'}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-08-30 21:59:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-08-30 21:59:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Allow Hacking 0.7.x or newer

This ensures that gating checks for the Python 2.x->3.x
comaptibility issues as well as other common errors.

The fixes for the newly added warning H202 are from
Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com> and are included
here:

db.py:                    Raise ValueError instead of Exception
internal_client.py:       Check for UnexpectedResponse instead of
                          Exception
test_swob.py:             Don't use locals() in string formatting
wsgi.py:                  Raise BindTimeout instead of Exception
test_utils.py:            Raise a test exception instead of Exception
proxy/controllers/obj.py: Raise SwiftException instead of Exception
                          We also check for an explicit TypeError
                          exception in the tests, where appropriate,
                          instead of Exception.

Change-Id: I4c8495abf407b6dbd0a4aa3627187d8b8544379e

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-27 22:27:56.000000000', 'message': "Report compute node free disk correctly for shared storage

For shared instance storage, we report the amount of free disk on
the shared filesystem one per host. This means that the cluster's
overall belief of the amount of disk free is very wrong, as the
disk is being reported multiple times.

Instead, we should count the number of users of a filesystem, and
then report the usage numbers for that filesystem divided by the
number of users.

DocImpact: this should probably be covered in the operations
manual.

Change-Id: Ia3f34ba8f1b2cd670666ad5f1cca2ee7dce91da7
Closes-Bug: #125232
"}]
commit_message:
Report compute node free disk correctly for shared storage

For shared instance storage, we report the amount of free disk on
the shared filesystem one per host. This means that the cluster's
overall belief of the amount of disk free is very wrong, as the
disk is being reported multiple times.

Instead, we should count the number of users of a filesystem, and
then report the usage numbers for that filesystem divided by the
number of users.

DocImpact: this should probably be covered in the operations
manual.

Change-Id: Ia3f34ba8f1b2cd670666ad5f1cca2ee7dce91da7
Closes-Bug: #125232

commit_message:
Corrected incorrect message: "Error: Failed to delete subnet" when deleting port.

Updated the file /horizon/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/networks/ports/tables.py
so it will give the correct error message when trying to delete a port that is in use.
This updated error message will give the same information as when using the command-line.

Change-Id: I7c6146c962edccb41dc978115999aae9782ae347
Closes-Bug: #1251314

commit_message:
Adding Read-Only volume attaching support to Nova

Adding mode argument to OpenStack API volumes extension (v2 and v3)
Allow end user using read-write or read-only mode to attach a volume to
an instance.

blueprint read-only-volumes

Change-Id: I28237ea4eb498acce7133e9f3b7b233f7fa6033e
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Ignore swap files generated during file edting by vim

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with .*.sw?

Change-Id: I11965d5fb22aeae622dad8bb29cf1f0533ed439a
Closes-Bug: #1255876

commit_message:
Adds "list hosts" test case - Cinder

This submission adds a new test script in volume admin api catogery,
so as to verify list hosts functionality in cinder API. Also added
required support functions in the corresponding files of both JSON/XML
interfaces.

Implements blueprint: cinder-grizzly1-blueprints-implementation

Change-Id: I72cdcb0f562a2706e400bfd6245a69c8368c2c2f

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw?

Change-Id: I1f3ee52050ac6812c34357ad786fd8210f4238f2
Closes-Bug: #1255876

commit_message:
Refactor assertEqualXML into a testtools matcher

Not all tests inheriting from TestCase will need to check XML equality.
Moving this functionality to a matcher leaves it up to the test class to
decided whether or not it needs it.

Change-Id: Ib28ec3b5dd96f662ce0cd90c650434b24c63ad6c
Related-Bug: #1226466

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-19 02:47:09.000000000', 'message': "Update memcache to match global requirements for stable/havana

python-memcache prior to version 1.48 will leak memory due to always
caching cas ids (compare and set) and with nothing designed to clean
it up.  In 1.48 it was changed to require a boolean argument 'cache_cas'
on init to enable the cas id caching.  In the case of keystone, we rely
on the cache_cas argument and cas functionality.  Ideally, all uses of
memcache should use later than 1.47 to prevent the memory leaking of
cas id caching.

Change-Id: I656a70a70342745d77dc285e338a0430852e8e0a
"}]
commit_message:
Update memcache to match global requirements for stable/havana

python-memcache prior to version 1.48 will leak memory due to always
caching cas ids (compare and set) and with nothing designed to clean
it up.  In 1.48 it was changed to require a boolean argument 'cache_cas'
on init to enable the cas id caching.  In the case of keystone, we rely
on the cache_cas argument and cas functionality.  Ideally, all uses of
memcache should use later than 1.47 to prevent the memory leaking of
cas id caching.

Change-Id: I656a70a70342745d77dc285e338a0430852e8e0a

commit_message:
Drop TEMPEST_LARGE_OPS_NUMBER by 33% to 100

The large-ops test was originally added to prevent regressions of bug
1199433. The number 150 was chosen somewhat arbitrarily because it never
failed on the cloud that it was tested on. But as we add more clouds and
AZs with different performance characteristics this test is starting to
fail.

Although failing this test at 150 is a sign that something is not
performant and doesn't scale well, this test is just here as a
regression test.  Separate bugs will be opened up for nova and neutron
about this issue.

Partial-Bug: #1257626
Partial-Bug: #1250168
Change-Id: Ie11bf4264eb1b26bc2445a99de7267b07b8058ce

commit_message:
Fix noVNC git repo

Recent change switched base git URL to git.openstack.org.
However, noVNC is only hosted on GitHub.
Change git repo URL for noVNC back to the GitHub one.

Change-Id: Iaa9f570639301be1c29cc400c1c73afcbf637b70

commit_message:
All API controllers inherit from wsgi.Controller

Most of the Cinder Public API Controllers inherit from wsgi.Controller,
but still some Cinder Public APIs controllers directly inherit from
object. So it's necessary to unify all the Cinder Public API Controllers
inherit from wsgi.Controller.
1. For code cleanup.
2. When we try to do body valid check in api's put/post method later, we
can use the helper function is_valid_body instead of using try...catch
block.

Change-Id: I88812224e0b182939cfccce63982cb8f95792891
Closes-Bug: #1257198

Controllers in API code used unicode() function which is not supported in Python3.
In order to be compatible with python2.x and python3.x unicode() function is

Change-Id: I98c7e566dba5befbfa794f9a7aa04301295b5ae2
Closes-Bug:  #1257929
'}]
commit_message:
Fix unicode() issue for Python3 compatibility

Controllers in API code used unicode() function which is not supported in Python3.
In order to be compatible with python2.x and python3.x unicode() function is
replaced by six.text_type() function.

Change-Id: I98c7e566dba5befbfa794f9a7aa04301295b5ae2
Closes-Bug:  #1257929

commit_message:
Remove text blobs from CSV output

Only output the descriptive text in the plain text writer, and not the
CSV writer.  This should make the CSV output more usable by something
wanting to automatically import it.

Change-Id: I56ccc4bdaa90069e81608f8f08ce1fd149de141e

commit_message:
xenapi: enable user interaction with stack.sh

In XenServer, devstack runs inside a virtual machine. This makes it hard
for the user to interact with stack.sh should a parameter be missing.
This change will create an upstart job (devstack) that runs
stack.sh with console enabled so user can interact with it by running
vncviewer or using XenCenter.

Logging the output is also disabled, stamp files are used instead to
detect the script run status in case install_os_domU.sh is used.

As run.sh.log is removed, standard devstack logging should be used.

The change also removes the environment settings from run.sh, as they
are not needed, they should be specified in localrc. This way user
cannot get different experiences by using unstack.sh/stack.sh or run.sh

Also a proper unstack.sh is called instead of killing screen in run.sh

Change-Id: I7eb12bd74746cc7a1db3aa9fd68ece645a50001d

commit_message:
Remove rpc service from agent manager

The agent doesn't need to act as a rpc server.
This patch migrate the agent manager from a rpc service to a normal service

Change-Id: I06f4546fa40f8702a75adc7f6f8e439d17af3de3

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-03 04:53:28.000000000', 'message': "Add conversion of JSON string to map in schema type MAP

A MAP schema's value is usually map.
However, a MAP schema's value is JSON string when using JSONParam.
It means conversion need in schema type MAP.

This implementation aims to provide the above conversion.

Fixes bug #1256891

Change-Id: I5acc1aa95c0c0e7bebc760d8bf088971630696ec
"}, {'created': '2013-12-03 11:05:09.000000000', 'message': "Return map parsed value at JsonParam.value

Currently, JsonParam returns String value as JsonParam.value.
However, SCHEMA_TYPES:MAP property doesn't support getting String value.
JsonParam have to return map value for to work properly.

Fixes bug #1256891

Change-Id: I5acc1aa95c0c0e7bebc760d8bf088971630696ec
"}]
commit_message:
Return map parsed value at JsonParam.value

Currently, JsonParam returns String value as JsonParam.value.
However, SCHEMA_TYPES:MAP property doesn't support getting String value.
JsonParam have to return map value for to work properly.

Fixes bug #1256891

Change-Id: I5acc1aa95c0c0e7bebc760d8bf088971630696ec

See my comment. I think when we have something like:

some_command | grep "$VAR"

we should first test that "some_command" did not fail, then try to grep. This way, the user can know whether "some_command" failed or if it just did not output what was expected.

Still, I +1 this patch because it seems helpful as is.'}, {'account_id': 8641, 'date': '2013-11-05 19:55:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Cyril, I'm totally agree with you. And it's also my first intent, when I try to solve the problem.

After a second thought, this would make each change need several extra lines: check $?, echo message, then grep. If we provide a common function for this, this would decrease the code readability.

Of a trade-off, I submit current patch with assertions.

Any better suggestions are warmly welcome."}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-11-06 12:34:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Rebuild Grizzly Object Storage Guide

We need to rebuild the Guide with the new clouddocs-maven-plugin.
The last rebuild did not work since we had no Jenkins job for this
guide, the job has now been added, so trigger a rebuild.

I just removed some extra whitespace from the pom file to trigger the rebuild.

Add some information in step 8 so it is not confusing any more.

backport: havana

(cherry picked from commit dd4380b127bc274211d7bba3b60b36b8bfa6baaa)

commit_message:
Clarify the step in image service install guide

When follows the instructions at "Install the Image Service in
OpenStack Installation Guide for Ubuntu 12.04 (LTS)  - havana".

In step 8, we have to add options to filter:authtoken section.
It is not clear though in glance-api-paste.ini what the contents
of the section should be, since it contains the option:
delay_auth_decision = true

Add some information in step 8 so it is not confusing any more.

Change-Id: Ib29c2138b115720e72bee5a13066c79158e188f7
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1255552
(cherry picked from commit dd4380b127bc274211d7bba3b60b36b8bfa6baaa)

commit_message:
Default name for ramdisks to image.

If you build a ramdisk with ramdisk-image-create and forget to specify
-o, you end up with a .kernel and .initramfs file as the image outputs.
This commit defaults the $IMAGE_NAME value to image so you'd end up
with image.kernel and image.initramfs

Change-Id: I10f3ac9ad178c32119523e4da930070e3ade4f73

commit_message:
Assert undercloud auth before building overcloud.

We now check that OS_PASSWORD is set before doing any work to build an
undercloud. Previously we would have likely taken the time to build an
image before failing on load-image.

Change-Id: I8b97cf57c3ac44b22afc35442cfeb535ea2637b8

commit_message:
Attempt to retrieve the vmdk descriptor data-pair

VMDK formats such as monolithicFlat and vmfs require two files to be
fully consumable by the Nova drivers (a descriptor-data pair: *.vmdk and
*-flat.vmdk).
On the upload of the descriptor (*.vmdk), upload_image.sh should attempt to
retrieve the *-flat.vmdk. The same way, the descriptor should be
retrieved when a flat disk is uploaded.
On success, the upload script will be able to use the flat disk as the image
content and the relevant descriptor settings as the image metadata.

Change-Id: I9214754029c46dd60b9e7d606d84d8819a498a8d
Closes-Bug: #1252443

[{'created': '2013-12-03 06:48:37.000000000', 'message': "Fix Storwize terminate_connection with no host

Nova may pass a connector to Cinder with no 'host' field, which was
causing a KeyError in the Storwize driver. This patch resolves this case
by doing the following:
1. If the volume is mapped to only 1 host, unmap it
2. If the volume was not mapped or mapped to multiple hosts, print a
   warning but don't raise an exception

Change-Id: I0ec1c24adbdfbcf1c4868b4981a2e2618d4b411c
Closes-Bug: #1244257
(cherry picked from commit 8185d1b5db421441ebba128f23f840a42f9bf050)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix Storwize terminate_connection with no host

Nova may pass a connector to Cinder with no 'host' field, which was
causing a KeyError in the Storwize driver. This patch resolves this case
by doing the following:
1. If the volume is mapped to only 1 host, unmap it
2. If the volume was not mapped or mapped to multiple hosts, print a
   warning but don't raise an exception

Change-Id: I0ec1c24adbdfbcf1c4868b4981a2e2618d4b411c
Closes-Bug: #1244257
(cherry picked from commit 8185d1b5db421441ebba128f23f840a42f9bf050)

commit_message:
Fix libvirt evacuate instance on shared storage fails

When evacuate instance which has config drive enabled on shared storage,
disk.config file can't be created because of permision error, chowns
disk.config if it already exists.

Change-Id: I20bafc3482ead30297ad5402a09e97141816f4d1
Closes-Bug: 1247526
(cherry picked from commit 3dfa2f9fd4a3084ae3fb8a7ba5d8a7458ae1c3bc)

commit_message:
Fix OLE error for HyperV

When run live-migration on HyperV, an OLE error
will occur. This is because we use wrong WQL
sentence when we try to query table
'Msvm_ResourceAllocationSettingData'.

This commit fixes the wrong WQL sentence.

Closes-Bug: #1246592

Change-Id: Iabb4096002a5be1fb930b077fbf5ef734893c258
(cherry picked from commit e74ceb68e1642d773f2ad0c655e6354f7a7fb362)

commit_message:
Fix incomplete translation of "Update members" widget

Marks the default value for the search fields of the "Update members"
widget translatable. Also updates the English PO file accordingly.

Change-Id: I8c317de49087b4207bcb774dd241fd1e4591882b
Closes-Bug: #1239927
(cherry picked from commit 3b79ec17b710000fa00523774ed2eff7dc1c12ca)

commit_message:
Role name should not be translated in Domain Groups dialog

Role names are retrieved from keystone and they should be displayed
as-is.

Change-Id: I62f9cb5582090e197fe2b7b434107dc801864571
Closes-Bug: #1255004
(cherry picked from commit 8ed32cc2785ffffbdcc0a2f0f745c10a226560fa)

commit_message:
GlusterFS: Set correct permissions for volume file created via clone

This is currently done when creating a new volume from scratch,
but not when cloning a new volume.

(cherry picked from commit 9c816aa0cf20ff0200831f58d8f14efb5e9e288e)
Closes-Bug: #1254768
Change-Id: I8506dc0824bacdb6cc42b4cadd41c2cad3a74b5b

commit_message:
GlusterFS: Synchronize operations that manipulate qcow2 data

Operations that modify qcow2 chains or the GlusterFS driver's
snapshot info file should use locking so that more than one thread
cannot run these operations at the same time.

Without this it is possible for multiple threads to concurrently
modify snapshot information resulting in an incomplete snapshot
chain.

Closes-Bug: #1251425

(cherry picked from commit 8a1fd8889170c289910944db016a4206fe5e1e32)
Change-Id: I93c6ffecd9aec38560cb19085243390b9120b363

[{'created': '2013-11-29 13:07:31.000000000', 'message': 'Pass the files correctly though the update mechanism

The files are critical to the definition of TemplateResources
so we need to have the correct copy of them in the backup, new and
existing stacks.

We need the existing (stack been updated) and the newstack to have
the same "files" but the previous must be old set (or empty).

'}, {'created': '2013-12-04 11:20:20.000000000', 'message': 'Pass the files correctly though the update mechanism

By "files", we mean the TemplateResource templates that get
passed into stack create and update.

The files are critical to the definition of TemplateResources
so we need to have the correct version of them in each stage
of the update.

Within the update there are 3 stacks:
- existing (stack been updated)
- newstack (the goal state)
- previous (a snapshot of the initial stack)

commit_message:
Pass the files correctly though the update mechanism

By "files", we mean the TemplateResource templates that get
passed into stack create and update.

The files are critical to the definition of TemplateResources
so we need to have the correct version of them in each stage
of the update.

Within the update there are 3 stacks:
- existing (stack been updated)
- newstack (the goal state)
- previous (a snapshot of the initial stack)

To update TemplateResources we need the existing stack to have access
to the new "files" but the previous stack must contain the old set (or empty).
This way the TemplateResource can get access to the new template and find the
difference to the previous template.

Note: although there are no tests in this patch, a following fully uses
and tests this functionality.

Partial-bug: #1254966
Change-Id: I803a385940759a4eb04df1eccce166be24ee333c

given that both testing.TestBase and MongodbMixin exposed

called in the storage tests for mongodb. This was consuming about
~19GB of storage per full suite run.

The problem was caused by _purge_databases not being overridden by the
MongodbMixin class. This likely has something to do with MRO, and
given that both testing.TestBase and MongodbMixin exposed
_purge_databases, the one *actually* being used was the
testing.TestBase default, null implementation.

The solution is to give precedence to the mixin class by including

Change-Id: Ia1abc4c6ec682f3d176f2093d45139f45f7ac12a
"}, {'created': '2013-12-03 17:35:17.000000000', 'message': "fix: mongodb tests consume storage like crazy

This patchset addresses a problem where _purge_databases wasn't being
called in the storage tests for mongodb. This was consuming about
~19GB of storage per full suite run.

The problem was caused by _purge_databases not being overridden by the
MongodbMixin class. It was a case of the diamond problem in an
inheritance graph. Here's the summary:

* testing.TestBase defines _purge_databases
* ControllerTestBase is a child of testing.TestBase
* XControllerTest are children of ControllerTestBase
* MongodbTestMixin was a child of object, and reimplements
  _purge_databases
* When MongoXControllerTest was presented with parents:
    - XControllerTest
    - MongodbTestMixin

  The MRO algorithm chose the implementation of _purge_databases that
  was first presented, in this case, the null implementation provided
  by testing.TestBase

The proposed solution for the time being is to have each of the
MongoXControllerTest classes to override the _purge_databases method.

Note: subtyping can get very messy.

Change-Id: Ia1abc4c6ec682f3d176f2093d45139f45f7ac12a
"}]
commit_message:
fix: mongodb tests consume storage like crazy

This patchset addresses a problem where _purge_databases wasn't being
called in the storage tests for mongodb. This was consuming about
~19GB of storage per full suite run.

The problem was caused by _purge_databases not being overridden by the
MongodbMixin class. It was a case of the diamond problem in an
inheritance graph. Here's the summary:

* testing.TestBase defines _purge_databases
* ControllerTestBase is a child of testing.TestBase
* XControllerTest are children of ControllerTestBase
* MongodbTestMixin was a child of object, and reimplements
  _purge_databases
* When MongoXControllerTest was presented with parents:
    - XControllerTest
    - MongodbTestMixin

  The MRO algorithm chose the implementation of _purge_databases that
  was first presented, in this case, the null implementation provided
  by testing.TestBase

The proposed solution for the time being is to have each of the
MongoXControllerTest classes to override the _purge_databases method.

Note: subtyping can get very messy.

Change-Id: Ia1abc4c6ec682f3d176f2093d45139f45f7ac12a

commit_message:
fix(mongo): Delete claimed message fails

This patch adds an additional check on the primary node for the correct
claim ID if it fails to match on the secondary. This takes care of the
case when the claimed version of the message document has not yet been
replicated to the secondary before the client attempts to delete it.

Change-Id: Ia22562532351a36bedc980c7c6041517207b2723
Closes-Bug: #1247297

[{'created': '2013-11-29 10:50:43.000000000', 'message': 'Fix incorrect resp body on create snapshop_meta

Create metadata for a snapshot with key-value set, which key in uppercase
and lowercase(e.g.{"key": "v1", "KEY": "V1"), the server accept the
request and return the key-value set {"key": "v1", "KEY": "V1"}. But the
server just add one metadata because the server is case ignore now.

The patch will modify the resp body with the one which the server added.

update_all has the same ploblem.

Change-Id: I684049412a4aa84f593e970c87157c74fffdfffe
Closes-Bug: #1255917

commit_message:
Fixes case insensitive for resp body

Create metadata for a snapshot with key-value set, which key in uppercase
and lowercase(e.g.{"key": "v1", "KEY": "V1"), the server accept the
request and return the key-value set {"key": "v1", "KEY": "V1"}. But the
server just add one metadata because the server is not case sensitive.

The patch will modify the resp body with the one which the server added.

update_all has the same ploblem.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I684049412a4aa84f593e970c87157c74fffdfffe
Closes-Bug: #1255917

commit_message:
feat(sharding): Cache shard mappings

This patch modifies sharding.Catalog so that it caches the mapping
between (project, queue) ===> shard. This reduces latency for
all data plane operations when sharding is enabled.

Change-Id: I54714c4e6c0ed78ac302ce86aed9bb72b200052b
Partially-Implements: blueprint storage-sharding

commit_message:
chore: Pass cache into drivers

This patch plumbs storage drivers so they all get a cache instance
they can use at their discretion.

I decided to make cache a required param to the initializers, since
any deployment of Marconi of any significance would likely opt to
enable caching anyway, and the cache library has a default in-memory
backend that can be used for simple deployments.

Note also that both data- and control-plane drivers receive a cache
instance, even though the sharding controllers will not use it
(caching will be done in the sharding data driver instead.) I thought
it would be better to pass cache in both cases so we can share test
code and avoid complicating utils.load_storage_driver(). Also, the
control driver may eventually support operations other than sharding;
cache may come in handy then.

Change-Id: I647791af0d7a5914c30cb2489033ec650a455370
Signed-off-by: kgriffs <kurt.griffiths@rackspace.com>

diskimage-builder defaults to ubuntu if you don't specify a base element (or at least some element that copies a file into the buildroot's /).

I'm fine to leave $NODE_DIST set in devtest.sh though, as I think it's better to be explicit.  The comment about $NODE_DIST being required isn't really accurate either, given the diskimage-builder behavior."}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-11-26 14:04:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

slagle: diskimage-builder is next'}, {'account_id': 1726, 'date': '2013-11-26 14:50:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Agree that a default ubuntu can be weird for some people, but a default should be provided so users have a working story from the begining. 

What about checking which distro is the user running and act based on that? Ubuntu users will prefer a ubuntu default one, and RH/Fedora ones a fedora default."}, {'account_id': 6449, 'date': '2013-11-26 16:30:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I like Ghe's idea and agree that would be the least surprising default for any given user."}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-11-26 16:52:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ghe: exactly. I was just thinking about coding up the same thing...

So given we actually need to do this here, triple-ci, and probably in diskimage-builder too where does the check belong?

It looks like we already do this in scripts/install-dependencies (check for distro type) so perhaps just refactor that bit out into a common script in the incubator.
And for now we could copy the same thing into diskimage-builder too. Does this seem reasonable?'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-27 01:15:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

diskimage-builder doesn't need a default; the Ubuntu default is already deprecated.

I don't think toci needs one either, it can/will be parameterised by jenkins/zuul. devtest is the special case."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-27 12:07:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Use set-os-type to set default NODE_DIST

Adds a new script called set-os-type which can be used
to export TRIPLEO_OS_FAMILY and TRIPLEO_OS_DISTRO in
your current environment.

Updates the devtest.sh script to call set-os-type and
then we can use the TRIPLEO_OS_DISTRO as the default
value for NODE_DIST.

Change-Id: I504b4c41a2fec6958fe16c8b2a2dcff6b719f70a

to pypi-mirror.

commit_message:
Use wheels for installation

Add an option to pbr to use wheels when installing things from pip. The
speed boost this gives is quite sexy, as it can avoid having to
re-build C things all the time.

Change-Id: Id9b9b21ef949ff44c7c962e81576266661264a13

commit_message:
Add script to install a testenv client

This commit adds a new script testenv-client, who purpose is to call
a gearman function "lockenv" passing it the name of a unique callback
gearman job, the callback when called can be used to run a command
while the test environment remains in a locked state.

This is intended to be used by tripleo-ci to lock test environments while
being used.

Change-Id: I5d552a1a8571f6ce0514c535f064e238d37dbc1f

commit_message:
Add element to install a testenv worker

This element adds a new script testenv-worker, who purpose is to register
itself with a gearman broker. When called it holds the test environment
lock while it calls back to the client using a gearman callback job. The
callback job is passed data describing the test environment. Once finished
the original job is completed, freeing up the environment.

This is intended to be used by tripleo-ci to discover and lock test
environments.

Depends on I170ee12955263065a4adff4221e5bc60015cae70

Change-Id: I79323cb78edfcea7a7d56d9cd507354ea420ee65

commit_message:
Check paths and display a good error message if non existent.

Currently when the paths to needed SSL files are invalid an awkward
message is displayed to the user.  This patch more clearly directs
a user at a problem.

Currently the devstack bug:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/devstack/+bug/1168555
is preventing this from passing Jenkins tests.

Fixes bug: 1160520

Change-Id: I070870ea6c0f8a754a8e164a362a1fd33e750105

commit_message:
Clarify the step in image service install guide

When follows the instructions at "Install the Image Service in
OpenStack Installation Guide for Ubuntu 12.04 (LTS)  - havana".

In step 8, we have to add options to filter:authtoken section.
It is not clear though in glance-api-paste.ini what the contents
of the section should be, since it contains the option:
delay_auth_decision = true

Add some information in step 8 so it is not confusing any more.

Change-Id: Ib29c2138b115720e72bee5a13066c79158e188f7
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1255552

commit_message:
API ports update for WSME 0.5b6 compliance

This makes use of the mandatory option of WSME, to remove some of the
custom validation code. The patch also includes a new attribute on
Ports API object called node_uuid to store the UUID of the node that
Port belongs to, once this field is set it magically converts the UUID
to the numeric ID of the node and sets the node_id attribute to be
used internally.

Change-Id: I973987de48fa008f5752861a2acfaf819f80e2ad
Partial-Bug: #1252213

commit_message:
Add deploy ramdisk element for Ironic

Ironic requires callback from deploy ramdisk via API with json data.
Auth token also required if Keystone auth enabled for Ironic API.
This patch adds separate element 'deploy-ironic' for Ironic deploy
ramdisk creation.

Change-Id: I5ef96711763e50307cfa17c406a9e16bffb937bc

commit_message:
Change db_uri to hand out UTF8 MySQL URIs

MySQL databases normally default to use whatever
character set is read from the global config.
OpenStack projects expect to be working with a unicode
charset database, so lets make sure that assumption is
true by explicitly stating UTF8 in the connection string.

Closes-Bug: 1257056

Change-Id: Iac63b40f603d1144ae3c6575b372ad586dabd4b9

commit_message:
Added Sample priority

With the routing notifier we can now issue high-frequency notifications
and not worry about clogging up the queue. The Sample priority will
be used for this situation.

Change-Id: I612c4ba414b0cb932873e09543c3ea281cd44919

commit_message:
Add diskimage-builder element.

Installs diskimage-builder from git. It's useful to have this in an
image since cloud instances themselves are often good build hosts to run
diskimage-builder (large amounts of ram for tmpfs, etc). Especially if
you have limited resources locally.

I considered adding this to the diskimage-builder repo instead of
tripleo-image-elements. If feedback suggests the other way, I'll submit
a patch for diskimage-builder instead.

Change-Id: I237ad800255d1ba927bfaa15c44dc352589b2df8

commit_message:
Routing notifier

Takes a yaml-based config file
(see etc/oslo/routing_notifier.yaml.sample) via
routing_notifier_config option.

Events may be routed by priority or event_type.

Drivers are loaded via entry-points (must be copied
to target project setup.cfg)

Specific drivers may be disabled via
disabled_notification_driver option.

This will be ported to oslo.messaging next.

Change-Id: I4d21e1ce62f102c1f25395dddfbe1310cec655ba

commit_message:
Ensure we check func() at least once after sleep()

Looking at some logs the while loop seems to be "stuck" during sleep
for a long time and we just exit the loop w/o calling func() causing
failures in Neutron large-ops test for example. So re-writing the
loop so we call func() at least once after a sleep and do the timeout
check after the call to func()

Change-Id: Iba4b37d9db221dbc1069e607b65eed74700429d9
Closes-Bug: 1254890

commit_message:
Try decoding string to UTF-8 on error message fail

Database Errors from SQLAlchemy tend to get mangled into ASCII. If an
error is process that contains UTF-8 data in ASCII form if fails to
build the message and will lead to a 5xx error. Catch the error and try
to decode it to create the message again, if that doesn't work at least
fail gracefully.

Change-Id: Iecb1170387c51064918780dc6de07db7ca8aeeee
Closes-Bug: 1253905

commit_message:
Add exact filter support to SQL API list stacks

Uses a dict of KEY:VALUE to compare values of VALUE against database
attribute KEY and return matching stacks.  If VALUE is a list, tuple,
set, or frozenset, this will evaluate to an IN clause instead.

blueprint: filter-stacks
Change-Id: If68edd9eaad3fe2ec4d11831d9eda9798a490e89

commit_message:
Use six for iter keys/values

Both iter keys and values have different names in Python 2 and Python3.
See http://pythonhosted.org/six/#object-model-compatibility
Mapping for iterkeys() and itervalues():

   six               Python 2           Python 3
   six.iterkeys(dict)   dict.iterkeys()    dict.keys()
   six.itervalues(dict) dict.itervalues()  dict.values()

Implemenets blueprint make-py3x-compatible

Change-Id: Iddfdb5a04be0416f8678bfa1ee96f68f88d41a78

I'm curious if any other reviewers have thoughts about just always sending {} as the context?

I'm worried about the future cases where we will not have a context available to send with notifications, for example in the asynchronous tasks processing. The damage would be if someone is writing scripts downstream of the notifications and starts to depend on http stuff being available in the context--it sounds kind of like tight coupling to me."}, {'account_id': 6484, 'date': '2013-12-03 13:20:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

@markwash, I can't see any strong justification to hide the context if we can provide it. Because it maybe used by other upper layer consumers, like Ceilometer for metering. And I don't think there is any backwards compatibility given we'd providing more and won't impact current info we are provided. Just my 2 cents about this.

[{'created': '2013-11-21 13:52:04.000000000', 'message': "Migrate to oslo.messaging

Glance currently uses a custom notifier and it has been maintaining it
for a long time. In a hope of reducing duplicated code and improving
cross-project contributions, this patch replaces the old notifier with
the one, recently developed, in oslo.messaging.

The oslo.messaging project is a port of the old oslo-rpc code to a
standalone, more stable and improved project. It brings all the benefits
that oslo-rpc would've brought as well as an easier way to integrate
with other projects.

This patch also:

    - Reduces the code shipped along with Glance since all the code
      copied from oslo-incubator related to the notifier is not needed
      anymore.
    - Improves the stability of existing, broker based, notifications.
    - Brings HA support.
    - Keeps backward compatibility by translating the old
      `notifier_strategy` into oslo.messaging drivers.

Changes to the code:

    - It is now necessary to pass the request context to the
      notification call.
    - Notifier package is no longer necessary. A notifier module was
      added instead.
    - New, notifier related, configurations were added.
    - A lot of code was removed

Since there's still not an official release, requirements.txt points to
the latest tarball created. A release for oslo.messaging is planned for
Icehouse.

docImpact
Implements bp oslo-messaging

Change-Id: I8cd84772bc5867e06b2a50ed7e15b9e86f0b94ad

commit_message:
Migrate to oslo.messaging

Glance currently uses a custom notifier and it has been maintaining it
for a long time. In a hope of reducing duplicated code and improving
cross-project contributions, this patch replaces the old notifier with
the one, recently developed, in oslo.messaging.

The oslo.messaging project is a port of the old oslo-rpc code to a
standalone, more stable and improved project. It brings all the benefits
that oslo-rpc would've brought as well as an easier way to integrate
with other projects.

This patch also:

    - Reduces the code shipped along with Glance since all the code
      copied from oslo-incubator related to the notifier is not needed
      anymore.
    - Improves the stability of existing, broker based, notifications.
    - Brings HA support.
    - Keeps backward compatibility by translating the old
      `notifier_strategy` into oslo.messaging drivers.

Changes to the code:

    - It is now necessary to pass the request context to the
      notification call.
    - Notifier package is no longer necessary. A notifier module was
      added instead.
    - New, notifier related, configurations were added.
    - A lot of code was removed

Since there's still not an official release, requirements.txt points to
the latest tarball created. A release for oslo.messaging is planned for
Icehouse.

docImpact
Implements bp oslo-messaging

Change-Id: I8cd84772bc5867e06b2a50ed7e15b9e86f0b94ad

The patch makes sqlite database connection lazy.

If the sqlite connection is created in a thread and then accessed from
another one, it'll fail mentioning that the connection is not thread
safe and that sqlite objects should be accessed from within the thread
the connection was created in.

Creating the connection instance at the very end alleviates this issue
but it doesn't fix it completely. It is still possible to create a
connection in a sub thread and then access it from another one. This

commit_message:
Make sqlite connection lazy

The patch makes sqlite database connection lazy.

If the sqlite connection is created in a thread and then accessed from
another one, it'll fail mentioning that the connection is not thread
safe and that sqlite objects should be accessed from within the thread
the connection was created in.

Creating the connection instance at the very end alleviates this issue
but it doesn't fix it completely. It is still possible to create a
connection in a sub thread and then access it from another one. This
patch just makes that less probable by creating the instance when it's
actually needed.

Closes-bug: 1257093

Change-Id: I2ce46c20158fbf090a25736b3afc1dd32437af24

commit_message:
Require python-cinderclient >= 1.0.6

Havana Nova should require python-cinderclient 1.0.6, which includes
support for features implemented in Havana and already being used by
Nova.  (APIs for assisted snapshots, and volume migration.)

(Landed in master in commit 831c7e6d.)

Change-Id: Ie2efb90a6e8b985f9bb8f9604eedd84e0d8a8a45
Closes-Bug: #1230925

commit_message:
Avoid clobbering {system_,}metadata dicts passed to instance update

Right now, the dicts for metadata items passed to instance_update
methods will get clobbered as part of the save. This patch makes
a copy before doing the update to avoid this.

Change-Id: I546692779a7467c5cb309059bb46a9bc9b62d5f1
(cherry picked from commit bbe2c5f08f52b1080a857a7e59c227587aa89717)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-02 13:57:13.000000000', 'message': "run_test.sh -V --unit doesn't run using virtualenv

Before this change, when you called the script using the -V option, the tests
were run outside the virtualenv that the script creates.
To fix it, I modified the lines of the script that run the tests to run
inside the virtualenv using the $wrapper variable.

Change-Id: I5c202727e0b5214670d54e14c80a68cc8ebec400
Closes-Bug: #1251730
"}]
commit_message:
run_test.sh -V --unit doesn't run using virtualenv

Before this change, when you called the script using the -V option, the tests
were run outside the virtualenv that the script creates.
To fix it, I modified the lines of the script that run the tests to run
inside the virtualenv using the $wrapper variable.

Change-Id: I5c202727e0b5214670d54e14c80a68cc8ebec400
Closes-Bug: #1251730

"}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2013-11-11 19:08:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Heya - I think we need to decide what happens on failure..

e.g. With 3 backends.. If backend number 2 fails, should we ignore and move onto number 3, revert the change in backend 1, or just stop and leave the three backends out of sync..

Our custom Akamai backend, which is essentially a hardcoded version of this, handles rolling back where necessary. To complicate things, the order of which backend is executed first (Akamai or PowerDNS) is different depending on the particular action. E.g. we create_domain in powerdns and then akamai, but delete_zone in akamai and then powerdns.

Anyway, food for thought..'}, {'account_id': 8864, 'date': '2013-11-11 19:47:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So there's two problems we need to solve:

1. What happens when a backend's method fails. Does making it user-configurable make sense? Ie, a onfail = continue/stop/revert setting? Should we make it configurable on a per-method basis?

2. How to handle order. Perhaps backends could declare order, so for example the Akamai backend would declare "my delete method needs to be called before powerdns's delete method", and "my create method needs to be called after powerdns's create method." To keep rewriting current backends to a minimum, the default would be the current ordering.

3. Something I didn't think of when coding this first patch is backend dependencies. For example, presumably Akamai depends on PowerDNS. NSD4-slave would also depend on PowerDNS. Should we enforce that, or leave it to the operator?'}, {'account_id': 8864, 'date': '2013-11-11 22:30:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Conversely, we could just limit multi-backend to a two-backend master-slave system, and let ordering be decided by the semantics inherent in a master-slave setup:

Deletes are done on the slave before the master

Creates/updates are done on the master before the slave

I can think of one use case where there could be more than two types backends: one backend for the PowerDNS master, another backend for a NSD4 slave, and another backend for a different slave. The rationale is to have heterogeneous slaves in case a serious security flaw is discovered in one, for example.

But this is still a master-slave setup, so as long as the above ordering is enforced between the master backend and the slaves backends, the order among the salves backends is unimportant.

To me this sounds like the way to go, unless we can think of a use case where the effort required to make fine-grained "call this method on this backend before this method on this backend" ordering control is worth it.'}, {'account_id': 8864, 'date': '2013-11-11 22:53:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-11 22:55:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

I think I like your idea of making the multi backend only handle 2 backends, then enforce "master" / "slave" semantics on the ordering .. It's going to cover the 95% use case without excess complication.

Let's go with your route :)'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2013-11-12 10:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Multi-backend

Multi backend implementation using the composite pattern. The
multi-backend is its own self-contained backend that simply dispatches
all methods to a master and a slave backend, with ordering described in
MultiBackend's docstring.

commit_message:
Fix flavor names with Amazon prefix "m1"

* Remove Amazon specific prefix "m1" from flavor names.
* Amazon has the M1 prefix to denote high memory, and it also denotes
  that thhe instance created from M1 instance types are based on Intel Xeon
  processors.
* "m1" doesnt have any similar meaning in OpenStack. We dont map flavors
  to any specific hardware platform. Hence removing the prefix.

Change-Id: Id54530ea6d58d19193702c5a0af55ca7d237b3dd
Closes-Bug: #1161988

commit_message:
Fix bug with no test status updating while standalone run.

Sometimes when single test from testrun is started or restarted its
status is not updated by nose storage plugin. In those conditions
session from nose storage plugin can not access data that were provided
by session of higher level in models.py logic of parent process.
Explicitly closing parent process session before start test running
does help but some additional code modification required in
this case.

Change-Id: Ie5415963c189b66cca58986370982f814f2a7431

commit_message:
Removes check CONF.dhcp_options_enabled from nova

* Neutron supports extra_dhcp_opts since Havana
* Hence remove boolean check dhcp_options_enabled

Closes-Bug: #1214162
DocImpact
Change-Id: I9af217a87a237e078e70332cbed1c80ad4d5db0a

commit_message:
Fix i18n error when resource-name is non-english

When executing commands about event and resource with
non-english resource-name, error "'ascii' codec can't
decode byte...." will occur.

Root cause is that heatclient can not generate a correct
encoded url. This Patch will use quote and safe_encode
functions to implement a url-encode process.

Closes-Bug: #1249234
Change-Id: I4261fdaf6ccc60aebdb9df236f4eedce0f9baa14

Matt: I replied to your inline comments. My plan is to compact the pre-Havana migrations in a patch series. As such many of your comments are out of scope for the changes here which only reflect compaction of 133 through 140.

Also, even though there are quite a bit of things we would like to change/refactor in the old 133_folsom.py migration we can't just do that because then new schema's wouldn't match (exactly).

Roman:

My testing process is outlined here:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Database_migration_testing

Additionally, we now have a nice tool in tools/db/schema_diff.py.

When I've compacted migrations in previous releases what I can say is that the schema's for MySQL and PostgreSQL matched what was there before compaction exactly."}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-10-29 13:14:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Victor: I choose the rename 133_folsom.py directly to 140_havana (skipping grizzly as you point out). Our goal is to compact all of the grizzly and havana migrations in this patch series so I figured renaming it now to Havana seemed reasonable.
