[{'created': '2013-10-28 20:10:43.000000000', 'message': 'Compact pre-Icehouse database migrations < 140.

Compacts the pre-Icehouse database migrations into a single
migration (140_havana.py).

Pre-Icehouse users will need to upgrade to Havana before
running any Icehouse migrations.

Tested on MySQL and PostgreSQL schemas on Fedora 19 to ensure the
new compacted migration generates an identical schema to the
previous migrate scripts in Havana.

Change-Id: I0405c02191a47b96759131bf6b7a1379f4b5711e
Implements: blueprint compact-havana-db-migrations
'}, {'created': '2013-10-30 16:22:52.000000000', 'message': 'Compact pre-Icehouse database migrations <= 140.

Compacts the pre-Icehouse database less <= 140 migrations into a single
migration (140_havana.py).

Pre-Icehouse users will now need to upgrade to Havana before
running any Icehouse migrations.

Tested on MySQL and PostgreSQL schemas on Fedora 19 to ensure the
new compacted migration generates an identical schema to the
previous migrate scripts in Havana.

Specific changes include:

1) Add counters to bw_usage_cache table.

2) Add node to instances.

3) Add indexes to instances.

4) Add indexes to migrations.

5) drop server name from instances
 NOTE: for sqlite this change recreated the instances table altogether.
 This required slight changes to the 201_add_sqlite_indexes.py migration
 to account for this change since we no longer need to add indexes
 there. 140_havana has been adjusted to accomidate this via a new
 common_indexes array... which moving forward we should use instead.

6) add indexes to fixed ips.

7) Drop unused postgresql volume sequences.

Change-Id: I0405c02191a47b96759131bf6b7a1379f4b5711e
Implements: blueprint compact-havana-db-migrations

commit_message:
Compact pre-Icehouse database migrations <= 140.

Compacts the pre-Icehouse database migrations <= 140 into a single
migration (140_havana.py).

Pre-Icehouse users will now need to upgrade to Havana before
running any Icehouse migrations.

Tested on MySQL and PostgreSQL schemas on Fedora 19 to ensure the
new compacted migration generates an identical schema to the
previous migrate scripts in Havana.

Specific changes include:

1) Add counters to bw_usage_cache table.

2) Add node to instances.

3) Add indexes to instances.

4) Add indexes to migrations.

5) drop server name from instances
 NOTE: for sqlite this change recreated the instances table altogether.

6) add indexes to fixed ips.

7) Drop unused postgresql volume sequences.

Change-Id: I0405c02191a47b96759131bf6b7a1379f4b5711e
Implements: blueprint compact-havana-db-migrations

commit_message:
Fix DB integrity issues when using postgres

The IntegrityError faced on network deletion that
spooks Tempest tests is most likely caused by the
fact that the ml2 plugin does a dirty read. By
adding a 'select for update' we should be able to
address the issue once and for all.

Also, there's a chance that the dhcp port gets
reallocated while we are deleting the network. To
this aim, catch the integrity error and attempt
to recover from it.

This patch also removes the handling of errors
on concurrent reads that can no longer occur when
deleting the network.

(Hopefully) Closes-bug: #1239637

PS: This fix may be relevant for bugs #1243726 and #1246737

Change-Id: Iefae7fc8a903cc35d8bf80fc4cee533b7f64032c
(cherry picked from commit 54d79acaab50993f08b50f21019f82f17d38caa3)

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw?

Change-Id: I9384015efdd1bc2a9bbfe6f25552cd909b155998
Closes-Bug: #1255876

subject: Remove mox usage from test_baremetal_nodes.py
messages:
[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-03 12:11:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-12-03 13:43:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

Please don't waste your own time and introduce needless code changes that are likely to break things doing this.

there are far bigger issues with porting to python 3 than mox, and there are more important things to be done - see nova bugs in launchpad for ideas.

As far as I am concerned - don't merge patches that do this."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-12-03 15:37:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There is a mailing list on the topic:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-November/018501.html

I don't believe the direction of nova is to move everything from mox to mock since it sounds like we can use mox3 to still use mox with python 3, but I'm not sure how much people have tried using it in nova yet (some of the client projects are moving to mox3 in icehouse).

For what it's worth, personally I write new tests with mock and try to refactor existing tests using mox to mock when working on a patch that touches existing tests (and if the refactor is trivial). I don't see that being the case here so I agree with Nikola that it doesn't need to be done."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-12-03 15:43:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Also, the plan is to eventually move the baremetal code to Ironic, so of all the things to refactor, the code that's planned to move out of tree is not a good starting point. :)"}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-12-03 15:43:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

commit_message:
VMware: add support for VM diagnostics

The drivers now return diagnostics for a requested VM.

Implements blueprint vmware-vm-diagnostics

VMware specific keys will be namespaced.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I08f199f7e3b4edafe60ce73d2fc833f8c5a5574e

commit_message:
Make db API respect context show_deleted

Currently the soft-delete aware stuff in the DB api only respects
flags passed in directly, not the context.show_deleted, so align
the code with what is implied by existing comments and respect
the flag in the context too.

Change-Id: I88cd1a8862a2a53c314849e11d026182180bce9b
blueprint: request-scoping-policy

commit_message:
Fix i18n messages in neutronclient

Using tools/check_i18n.py to scan source directory, and fix most of
the errors.
    - Message internationalization
    - First letter must be capital
    - Using comma instead of percent in LOG.xxx

Partial-Bug: #1217100
Change-Id: I312f999f97e33d84c3f06fa1caacf32affc26a78

commit_message:
Test MAC address should be 6 octets.

Since nova commit Idcba745a011604d7664b62d88f1dede88d10443d, the nova
api now validates MAC addresses.  The test MAC address we were using in
register-nodes was not valid.

Change-Id: I0e60a20e503098532b81c5ee7942e99f0180a4f9

commit_message:
Extend devtest_overcloud timeout by 5 minutes

We have seen that the overcloud is taking a bit longer to come up for
some reason. This change gives it 5 more minutes.

Change-Id: I32dccf4649bec6b5301584d30d08b9fa961dc572

commit_message:
Add config option to limit image members

This patch adds the image_member_quota config option. This allows a deployer
to limit the number of image members allowed per image. The default value
is 128, to be consistent with other quota defaults. Users will only be able
to update an image if the result of the transaction would be under this limit.

This is for both Glance v1 and v2

Fixes bug 1252459
docImpact

Change-Id: I02f5e82ca4c4acf6cd7bc94f9b99086054a616c9

commit_message:
Revert "ML2 plugin should not delete ports on subnet deletion"

This reverts commit 0d131ff0e9964cb6a65f64809270f9d597c2d5d1

There is really no problem with this change. However, it is probably
triggering a port_update notification to the agent for each port
with an allocated IP.
The agent handles that notification in a way which might be improved
from a scalability perspective.

I don't actually want this change to removed, I am just checking
whether neutron without it passess jobs.

Change-Id: I5494b607127b261043dcddfdc10c93a28ec20af5
Related-Bug: 1253896
Related-Bug: 1254236

commit_message:
ML2 plugin should not delete ports on subnet deletion

On subnet deletion ports are deleted asynchronously by dhcp agent
so plugin doesn't need to delete them itself.
Instead Ml2Plugin.delete_subnet() method should call update_port()
for each allocation to remove the IP from the port and call the MechanismDrivers.
The patch also adds subnets test suite from test_db_plugin to test_ml2_plugin.

Closes-Bug: #1246737
Change-Id: I7cf0461e9a3cfec4921e2de41fb1ab3fc119fddc

commit_message:
Refactors network test in scenario to support advanced network test

1. Adds VM connectivity check test between VMs in the same subnet.
2. Adds VM connectivity check test after VM resized.

Change-Id: I03988777be3f3a7ac363eb6d28c5d8dde866a259

@jd__, I'll modify that."}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2013-09-02 01:50:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@jd__, I don't think it's a very good way to add the resources information into each pollster as its attribute. Say we have a single pollster which is used in 2 different pipelines, pipeline1 and pipeline2. In pipeline1, it's defined to poll from resource1 every 60 seconds, while in pipeline2, it's defined to poll from resource2 every 10 seconds. In our current pipeline design, a single pollster instance object is used for all both pipelines, so there is no easy way for pollster to tell under which pipeline it is being invoked, hence to know the pipeline's resources definition. So I think it's better to have the PollingTask to pass the resources information to pollster's get_samples method. Any comment?

I'll modify the code to deal with [] resources situation."}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2013-09-02 03:47:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-02 03:58:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Works for me

This is the first building block of adding basic monitoring for physical
devices, which is like the central-agent but polls the metrcis from
physical devices.

Also expand the pipeline manager to deal with host definitions which
would used by the hardware-agent. The host definitions should be put as
the second document in the pipeline configuration file, while the
original pipeline definitions remains as the first document in the file.

Part of the blueprint monitoring-physical-devices.

Rebased on the original code at https://github.com/graflu0/ceilometer
contributed by Lucas and Toni.

Change-Id: Ia56e74626f700c9bd647bf73584e98f6cf39f207
Signed-off-by: Lucas Graf <graflu0@students.zhaw.ch>

commit_message:
Adding hardware-agent

This is the first building block of adding basic monitoring for physical
devices, which is like the central-agent but polls the metrcis from
physical devices.

This patch also add an optional field 'resources' to pipeline
definition. It could be a list of resource URI from which the hardware
agent pollsters should poll from.

Part of the blueprint monitoring-physical-devices.

Based on the original code at https://github.com/graflu0/ceilometer
contributed by Lucas and Toni.

Change-Id: Ia56e74626f700c9bd647bf73584e98f6cf39f207
Signed-off-by: Lucas Graf <graflu0@students.zhaw.ch>
Signed-off-by: Toni Zehnder <zehndton@students.zhaw.ch>
Signed-off-by: Lianhao Lu <lianhao.lu@intel.com>

commit_message:
Reduce boilerplate code using get_client_manager

There are a few Tempest tests that contain boilerplate code used
to create an Openstack manager client. This commit removes this
boilerplate code with the following changes:

1. BaseTestCase.get_client_manager now generates different
   credentials based on the type of user type passed in. There
   are also optional keyword arguments to control the type of
   manager to be instantiate as well as an alternate manager type
   in case tenant isolation is disabled.

2. Updated all tests that are using tenant isolation to use the
   updated get_client_manager method

Closes-Bug: #1246932
Change-Id: I098fac5f7c475cab92f016fb98f55ad695bf945f

(1 inline comment)

Julien - see inline for the use case of basing TransportURL on a ConfigOpts object.

What's the big picture of what you're trying to do here? What's the use case for avoiding use of a config object?"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-11-14 10:22:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

I've been discussing it with Doug last week. I think that oslo.messaging should be 'messaging', and that it should not rely on oslo.config.

I want to use oslo.messaging in application that do not have nor use configuration file (objects). So I'm trying to move the configuration part that is needed for OpenStack to a different layer."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-18 07:06:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

(1 inline comment)

Julien:

 > I've been discussing it with Doug last week. I think that oslo.messaging should be 'messaging', and that it should not rely on oslo.config.

Well, that I disagree with - the key design goal for the API of this library is that it works well for all the common users of oslo-incubator's RPC code.

I have no interest in prioritizing a not-yet-existing-user of this code over all the existing users of the code.

 > I want to use oslo.messaging in application that do not have nor use configuration file (objects). So I'm trying to move the configuration part that is needed for OpenStack to a different layer.

Which application is this?

I see APIs which cater for these type of applications to be secondary to the common users of oslo.messaging - I've no problem figuring out a way of doing it, but not at the expense of the common use case

One difficult issue to consider is https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+bug/1250737

The configuration options are not part of the API of the library. The existence of e.g. conf.rpc_backend is not something you can code your application against. This is something we only make guarantees to the users who are editing configuration files.

That's important, because it allows us to change the names and semantics of config options so long as we retain compat for older config files. Because it's not part of the API of the library, we don't need to worry about older users of the API.

So, we can consider making cfg.ConfigOpts optional by adding e.g.

  class MessagingConfig(object):

      ...

      def register_opts(self, opts, group=None):
          pass

      @property
      def rpc_backend(self):
          ...

but the downside of this would be we cannot simply rename rpc_backend in this class when we rename it for cfg ... I wouldn't rule it out completely for that reason, though

Moving to -2 for now - I think we need a better discussed high-level plan (i.e. a blueprint) for this work before tackling it piecemeal."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-26 06:03:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-26 06:03:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

commit_message:
transport: simplify TransportURL constructor

This avoids making the TransportURL class needing a configuration object
altogether. The long term plan is to remove/deprecate all the
configuration object needing in transport.

Change-Id: Ifc6b8cad1b86bc8290796d59478ddfcf79c1f705

commit_message:
"publicurl" should be required on endpoint-create

publicurl field is required and cannot be empty when create a endpoint in
keystone server.So the "--publicurl " also should set as mandatory in
keystoneclient.

Change-Id: Ia397c79a28dd3a6ddef141df0f7df30cc0bf7b6c
Closes-Bug: #1246335

commit_message:
Fix flavor names with Amazon prefix "m1"

* Remove Amazon specific prefix "m1" from flavor names.
* Amazon has the M1 prefix to denote high memory, and it also
  denotes that thhe instance created from M1 instance types are based on
  Intel Xeon processors.
* "m1" doesnt have any similar meaning in OpenStack. We dont map
  flavors to any specific hardware platform. Hence removing the prefix.

Change-Id: I4f71569cfb96255122db581b140addc0f25e87fa
Closes-Bug: #1161988

commit_message:
Move console scripts, use entry points

This will allow for unit testing of the console scripts,
and uses pbr to manage entry points for them.

/opt/stack/cinder/bin/* scripts may be removed after
devstack is updated to call /usr/bin/cinder* instead.

Change-Id: I70cad15380be6506eea11a08826e9906ff365884

Exception handle on unreachable trove-api

And there can be one dreadful corner case when the host provided in this AZ extension is different from what is in the extra specs of the volume type end user wants to use, which ends up with 'NoHostFound'creation failure."}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-08 14:32:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks Avishay ;-)

Yes, simple scheduler already support this, but I think the way it was doing was not good enough as it do the logic of get force host in scheduler.

I would propose that we do the logic in api part just like nova, and we can then enhance this to support ignore host in future.'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-12 04:34:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Zhiteng, any comments on this? Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2013-11-12 08:31:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I have been thinking about this in the past few days: whether we should have a quick/simple shortcut to by pass scheduler, to do _manual_ resource placement, for whatever reasons.

As a developer, I do find it useful to have such shortcut/backdoor to specify a host/back-end in creating instance/volume when debugging.  But as operator, no, no way I will allow my end users to put resource wherever they want.  I'd rather claim that 'end user cannot create volume directly on a host' as a feature than a bug.

I have several reasons that we don't need/want a shortcut like this:
1) I don't like the idea that end users is able to directly access internal resource (host/back-end) in end-user facing API.  Having such interface could possibly introduce security issues, for example, malicious users may probe the implementation details by exhaustive trying.  What makes it worse is, in current implementations (Cinder simple scheduler or Nova internal compute API), there's no way to turn this shortcut/backdoor off.
2) There are circumstances that admin/ops ppl may need to do this kind of stuff.  So here are indirect alternatives can do the same thing, well, at least do what we wanted (controlling resource placement the way we want).  As mentioned earlier, volume type can do it. Volume type is clean & nice abstraction that hides implementation details like host/back-end info from end users.  And creating volume types requires admin role which means end users cannot fool around it.  Besides volume types, there's also scheduler hint can do it as well (something like --scheduler_hints '"query": [ "volume_backend_name", "=", "HOST_I_WANT"]').  And scheduler hint together with json filters are both able to be turned off to avoid abusing.  These alternatives are not as straightforward as is the 'az:host' way, but they work.  Even though they require some extra effort and have some dependencies but they are safer, and that's the price to I am willing to paid.
3) Someone else (Nova in this case) has this feature is not a reason.

What these sounds reasonable?

BTW, the way it supports az:host in simple scheduler is directly copied from Nova, which had removed simple scheduler 1 year ago.  And the reason Nova has this shortcut in the first place when it came out, IIRC, was to maintain feature parity to AWS or Eucalyptus.  That's not a burden Cinder should carry.  You know what I am thinking propose to remove that from Nova, at least to make it optional/be-able-to-turn-off.'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-12 09:03:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks Zhiteng.

I was thinking if we can move make this action as Admin only action, thus no security issue.

I know that we can use volume backend and json filter to do the same thing, but those methods might not be straight forward enough for an admin.'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2013-11-12 09:10:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Sorry, I still don't see the value of introducing another admin API just because alternatives we have been using are not straightforward enough."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-20 06:03:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Enable create volume on force hosts

Cinder scheduler will help select host for create request based on
scheduler filters, but end user cannot create volume directly on a
force host.

This patch enhanced the option of "--availability-zone" for
"cinder create" to provide force hosts option. If end user specify
"--availability-zone zone1:host1", this means that customer want to
create the volume on force host host1.

Implements bp cinder-force-host

Change-Id: Ie281215bd18e015f3a8b41293fc1004181a5933e

[{'created': '2013-11-25 18:20:05.000000000', 'message': "Fixes Hyper-V snapshot spawning issue

In Hyper-V, snapshoting an instance and then spawning a new
one using the resulted snapshot image with the same flavor,
will result an Hyper-V Exception.

Hyper-V will get the request to resize the base image to it's
actual size, leading to an error.

The reason is that the logic of the resize_vhd method has been
changed, as it is meant to resize images to the flavor size minus
the image metadata size, thus it's maximum internal size. For this
reason, the way to decide whether the root image should be resized
or not must also be changed.

So, instead of comparing the root image and base image sizes,
we should compare their maximum internal sizes.

Closes-Bug: #1234759

(cherry picked from commit 751b7ecb58cb16964509f1d9a30eacadacfdf253)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/test_hypervapi.py

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V snapshot spawning issue

In Hyper-V, snapshoting an instance and then spawning a new
one using the resulted snapshot image with the same flavor,
will result an Hyper-V Exception.

Hyper-V will get the request to resize the base image to it's
actual size, leading to an error.

The reason is that the logic of the resize_vhd method has been
changed, as it is meant to resize images to the flavor size minus
the image metadata size, thus it's maximum internal size. For this
reason, the way to decide whether the root image should be resized
or not must also be changed.

So, instead of comparing the root image and base image sizes,
we should compare their maximum internal sizes.

Closes-Bug: #1234759

(cherry picked from commit 751b7ecb58cb16964509f1d9a30eacadacfdf253)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/test_hypervapi.py
	nova/virt/hyperv/imagecache.py
	nova/virt/hyperv/vmops.py

Change-Id: I83d2df76b726d705cedc52a8309a2be7037d6a79

commit_message:
Update openstack/common/lockutils

The following commits are in this update:

79e6bc6 fix lockutils.lock() to make it thread-safe
ace5120 Add main() to lockutils that creates temp dir for locks
537d8e2 Allow lockutils to get lock_path conf from envvar
d498c42 Fix to properly log when we release a semaphore
29d387c Add LockFixture to lockutils
3e3ac0c Modify lockutils.py due to dispose of eventlet
90b6a65 Fix locking bug
27d4b41 Move synchronized body to a first-class function
15c17fb Make lock_file_prefix optional
1a2df89 Enable H302 hacking check
b41862d Use param keyword for docstrings

Change-Id: I25a350b0f72e117e1beff92bba45f9c70c8cdc7c

The rebuild_server() function defined in the v2 and v3 base test
classes made some incorrect assumptions about variable scoping

commit_message:
Fix rebuild_server() function

The rebuild_server() function defined in the v2 and v3 base test
classes made some incorrect assumptions about variable scoping
because the method is set as a class method. This commit fixes this
method to behave properly so that it doesn't reference variables
outside it's scope.

Change-Id: I7d0ee6e0c0784952634b157187ca47f7afbcadf1

commit_message:
Migrate away from rackspace_resource

Having Rackspace specific resources subclass a the rackspace_resource
does not replace the clients system wide. Use the cloud_backend to
acomplish this. That way any special configuration done with pyrax
will be used in any client call.
Change-Id: Ia6d548e606a42c608135cb66876419d1b339a06c

commit_message:
Fix typo in keystone

1. Validate the user and tenant auth into in order to -> Validate the user
   and tenant auth info in order to
2. attmepting -> attempting
3. extnsion -> extension
4. identfier -> identifier
5. establed -> established
6. specifc -> specific
7. intitalized -> initialized
8. explicity -> explicitly
9. uniq -> unique

Change-Id: I8f4420e7c41cfdbc3f4751ed1c0b9a6e151b0940
Closes-Bug: #1254585

commit_message:
show diff between pip installed packages and requirements

This change will display the difference between which python packages pip
installed and the packages from the requirements lists.  It will print
the list of dependencies to the console (not including the directly declared
dependencies from the requirements list).

Closes-Bug: #1172417

Change-Id: I9363b50d6d7f5ef19c42bb2e30de45e352060ccd

Jamie, the blueprint is inadequate, basically it says using SSL is good, no argument there. But what's missing is:

1) Why isn't SSL possible at the moment?

2) What needs to be added to support SSL?

3) How do you plan to implement the missing functionality?

4) In what context is this valid? (i.e. only devstack).

5) How would the issue be solved outside the target context (i.e. outside devstack).

6) What are the underlying assumptions/requirements? (i.e. this only works with OpenSSL and it's configuration methodology).

7) Is this a general purpose solution or a one-off stepping stone to a better design?

8) What are the inherent problems with this approach? The design doesn't have to solve the problems but it should at least enumerate the issues so they can be taken into consideration and provide a historical context.

I can derive a fair amount of this from the patch set, but that's backwards, rather given the design I want to know if the patch set implements the design."}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-09-19 15:55:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

We should use Certmonger to do certs, even for the self signed use case:  https://docs.fedoraproject.org/en-US/Fedora/15/html/FreeIPA_Guide/certmongerX.html"}, {'account_id': 8116, 'date': '2013-09-19 16:05:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: No score

I'm confused. A quick perusal of the patch set suggests what is occurring is the distribution of the CA cert. But perhaps I'm wrong, that's why I wanted to blueprint to clearly the goal and solution.

My understanding of certmonger is it's functionality is the generation and renewal of certs. certmonger has to the best of my knowledge nothing to do with the distribution of certs, that's something else entirely.

Jamie please fill out the blueprint so we can all operate from the same set of assumptions without confusion."}, {'account_id': 8116, 'date': '2013-09-19 16:49:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Nalin Dahyabhai is the auther of certmonger, I sought clarification from Nalin on IRC as to the capabilities of certmonger.
I'm preserving the IRC conversation here for reference.

(12:11:45 PM) jdennis: nalin: question about certmonger functionality, my understanding was certmonger implemented the generation and renewal of certs, but it has no functionality
(12:12:05 PM) jdennis: for the distribution and installation of said certs, correct?
(12:13:33 PM) jdennis: in other words if certmonger is managing a CA cert some other mechanism has to be available to get that cert and it's trust into an OpenSSL ca bundle or a NSS database, yes/no?
(12:26:08 PM) nalin: jdennis: it stores certificates directly in NSS databases, so you shouldn't need an intermediate location for that. but for files, the assumption is that the certificate is the only content in the file, so you'd need to manually manage it if it was part of a bundle file
(12:27:44 PM) jdennis: nalin: tnx
(12:28:15 PM) nalin: sure
(12:28:40 PM) jdennis: nalin: wait a minute I think there might have been some confusion with my question
(12:30:00 PM) nalin: if by distribution you mean to other systems once they're stored to local files, then no, it doesn't know how to do that
(12:30:14 PM) nalin: (local files or NSS databases, that is)
(12:30:20 PM) jdennis: nalin: lets say certmonger generates a CA cert, it get's stored someplace (file, NSS db, etc.), but let's say you've got 10 other systems which need the CA cert in one or more locations, certmonger can't help with that right?
(12:31:06 PM) nalin: not directly, no. the most it can currently do is fire off a designated command after it stores the new certificate to disk
(12:31:47 PM) jdennis: that's primarily to handle renewal, correct?
(12:32:21 PM) nalin: the option was added to be used for that case, but it's not restricted to that case
(12:32:53 PM) jdennis: right, I could see it being used to initially populate
(12:34:13 PM) nalin: ... the list of trusted certs in VMs/containers, from the host?
(12:35:50 PM) jdennis: that's one use, another is cooperating services on different nodes using X509 auth with a common CA
(12:36:45 PM) nalin: are those nodes driving the renewal of their own certs, and if so, where would they be distributed to?
(12:37:47 PM) jdennis: that's one case, but the case I was specifically thinking of was renewal of the CA cert and it's distribution
(12:39:45 PM) nalin: that's going to be tricky, since we normally expect that deleting the old certificate is harmless if we're attempting to store the new one, and i don't think you'd generally want to do that with a CA cert
(12:41:27 PM) jdennis: but that's the province of the triggered external command run on renewal to get correct, not a consideration for certmonger
(12:42:07 PM) nalin: if you're pushing it from the location certmonger saves it to, out to somewhere else, sure. i'm talking about that first copy
(12:42:45 PM) jdennis: ah ok, understood"}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-09-20 06:20:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-09-20 06:27:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-20 06:57:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Allow deploying keystone with SSL certificates

Allow providing certificates through environment variables to be used
for keystone, and provide the basis for doing this for other services.
It cannot be used in conjunction with tls-proxy as the service provides
it's own encrypted endpoint.

Impletmenting: blueprint devstack-https
Change-Id: I8cf4c9c8c8a6911ae56ebcd14600a9d24cca99a0

Changes in devstack and nodepool will allow for pre-cached get-pip
script to be used, instead of downloading from the internets. Enable
the flag so that the cached script and the local mirror will be used
for pip installation.

Closes-Bug: #1254275
Change-Id: Ia5f69073f7f9bab9b5554185df5681fbd178b91d
'}]
commit_message:
Use get-pip for pip installation

Changes in devstack and nodepool will allow for pre-cached get-pip
script to be used, instead of downloading from the internets. Enable
the flag so that the cached script and the local mirror will be used
for pip installation.

Closes-Bug: #1254275
Change-Id: Ia5f69073f7f9bab9b5554185df5681fbd178b91d

commit_message:
Remove vim header

No need to set tabstop 189 times, this can be set in your vimrc file
instead.  Also if set incorrectly gate (pep8 check) will catch your
mistakes.

Change-Id: Ic6f0c0ef94e8194a5c121598305d1ec3c74e4843

[{'created': '2013-12-03 15:44:52.000000000', 'message': 'Unify different names between Python2/3 with six.moves

Some modules use different names in Python2 and Python3. Use six.moves
to make them work well in Python2 and Python3.
This is changes mapping:

six.moves      Python 2                 Python 3
builtins        __builtin__                 builtins
filter             itertools.ifilter()      filter()
reduce             reduce()                 functools.reduce()
reload_module  reload()             imp.reload()

commit_message:
Unify different names between Python2/3 with six.moves

Some modules use different names in Python2 and Python3. Use six.moves
to make them work well in Python2 and Python3.
This is changes mapping:

six.moves      Python 2       Python 3
reduce         reduce()      functools.reduce()

Implements: blueprint make-python3-compatible
Change-Id: I97971f2ab40385bfc2c73ae7e8a7620c4d64a03c

commit_message:
Ensure ml2 is set in core_plugin

When using ML2 plugin, we need to ensure that core_plugin flag
is set to the right class in neutron.conf.
This patch add documentaiton in init.pp and testing in the manifest to
ensure that the right plugin is configured.

Change-Id: I706db60dc07f468b920a9c3b233a5665df5a3a73
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Adds a debug flag to run_tests.sh

Using -d or --debug will run testtools instead of testr. This allows a
developer to use 'import pdb; pdb.set_trace()' to enter an interactive
debugging session.

Implements bp runtest-allow-debug

Change-Id: I13181f49e03e7c81b32763b2653eab4700db1e8c

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-02 20:28:44.000000000', 'message': "Fixed DB test cases on PyPy

They weren't working because of the intersection between some monkey
patching in the tests and the fact that ``sqlite3.Connection`` and
``Cursor`` are Python classes on PyPy, but C-extension classes on
CPython. The result was that trying to call the superclass's init
didn't work because the name ``sqlite3.Connection`` pointed to a
different class that wasn't actually the real superclass of
``GreenDBConnection``. Using ``super`` fixes this because the method
called is now always the real superclass's.

Change-Id: Ib45b16c7499883e560877788f13285d0a47cc2cd
"}]
commit_message:
Fixed DB test cases on PyPy

They weren't working because of the intersection between some monkey
patching in the tests and the fact that ``sqlite3.Connection`` and
``Cursor`` are Python classes on PyPy, but C-extension classes on
CPython. The result was that trying to call the superclass's init
didn't work because the name ``sqlite3.Connection`` pointed to a
different class that wasn't actually the real superclass of
``GreenDBConnection``. Using ``super`` fixes this because the method
called is now always the real superclass's.

Change-Id: Ib45b16c7499883e560877788f13285d0a47cc2cd

'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-11-25 00:43:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

Does it make sense to put transactions around single calls?"}, {'account_id': 7500, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:16:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Yes, Jamie, it "makes sense" to put a transaction around a "single call". Indeed, whether or not you explicitly demarcate the transactions, SQLAlchemy issues BEGIN and COMMIT commands. See the documentation on the autocommit flag. Thus, in the two examples you cite, the behavior would be the same if SQLAlchemy implicitly demarcated every query as a transaction.

Perhaps a more pertinent -- but certainly more subjective -- question is "should we favour explicit demarcation over implicit demarcation where the behavior is equivalent?" My opinion is that explicit demarcation is the best way to go. I have 2 reasons: (1) utility functions, such as _get_project, can be used for lone queries, such as by get_project, or as a part of a larger transaction, such as by list_user_ids_for_project, without conditional contortions ('if session is None' like in _get_metadata); (2) as a good practice to encourage correctness for future changes that introduce queries that require atomicity. I think reason (2) is especially pertinent given the indiscriminate use of transactions in this module prior to this patch.'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-11-26 19:00:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: No score

Not sure if i'm convinced, but i don't have the experience to argue database best practices if there really is a reason for it.

commit_message:
One transaction per call to sql assignment backend

There are numerous schedules that lead to inconsistent data in the
various grant tables and role table. These races arose from a lack of
synchronization during grant table modification (i.e., during grant
record creation + deletion and role deletion) and deletions of records
that grant records refer to (i.e., user, group, domain, and project
records). The races manifested as 404 errors in response to API
requests. This patch adds the necessary synchronization by way of
transactions.

Also removed pointless session.flush() calls at the ends of transactions.

Closes-Bug: #1246489
Change-Id: I958d48bafc7fcb95f1d9ea71e408b4cefc2469c9

commit_message:
Docs: layout our docs like the official openstack docs

Model the sections on http://docs.openstack.org/

Have the following sections:
- getting started
- install
- configure and run
- develop applications
- contribute

This will make future integration with the official docs easier and
it makes our docs more familiar to readers of openstack docs.

Change-Id: Ib84cfd4451b0e4e2569f8a3e027104d3457bb92e

commit_message:
Removes Unneeded mysql::server Dependency

Previously, the heat::db::mysql class contained a dependency on
mysql::server. This dependency is unneeded since mysql::db requires
mysql::config, which depends on mysql::server. Additionally, the
mysql::server dependency causes MYSQL HA installations such as
Galera to fail. Lastly, this aligns the class more closely with
the other [OPENSTACK_SERVICE]::db::mysql classes.

Change-Id: Ie6c4d3c8aaa531502bc5b9cd66a547f1f506385f

commit_message:
API: Fix the sensor_type and value

Convert everything to a string in the custom setter
as we don't know the order that the value and sensor_type are written,
so convert to the desired type in get_value().

part of blueprint api

'}, {'created': '2013-11-15 22:47:23.000000000', 'message': 'Object model with sqlalchemy subclasses

configurable backend that is similar, but not identical to the existing
db API model. Simple support for schema transition (for live upgrades)
and necessary work for remotability (with the exception of sqlalchemy
rehydration).

'}, {'created': '2013-11-18 19:36:33.000000000', 'message': 'Test the basic model and load an object backend on API start

in other commands.  Object model is then loaded after configuration
is parsed so that subclasses can choose behavior based on the config,
for instance, whether the new or old schema is in place.

The test cases cover basic persistence and object registry loading
unloading, more tests WIP

[{'created': '2013-11-27 13:42:51.000000000', 'message': 'Use channel_timeout for SSH connection timeout

Occasionally, SSH will get wedged so that a connection attempt is stuck
forever. When this happens, we need Tempest to abort the attempt and try
again. Currently, the individual connection timeout is set to the
overall timeout, so there will only ever be one attempt if this happens.
Using the channel_timeout instead will ensure that multiple connection
attempts are made even when the connection is wedged.

Fixes bug 1236524

Change-Id: Ie8dff41780bbf004cff5c880db202a8ae23a85c1
'}]
commit_message:
Use channel_timeout for SSH connection timeout

Occasionally, SSH will get wedged so that a connection attempt is stuck
forever. When this happens, we need Tempest to abort the attempt and try
again. Currently, the individual connection timeout is set to the
overall timeout, so there will only ever be one attempt if this happens.
Using the channel_timeout instead will ensure that multiple connection
attempts are made even when the connection is wedged.

Fixes bug 1236524

Change-Id: Ie8dff41780bbf004cff5c880db202a8ae23a85c1

messages:

'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-12-03 06:31:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think it's completely inappropriate for stuff like this:

 declare -x GNOME_KEYRING_CONTROL="/run/user/markmc/keyring-UiPefJ"
 declare -x GNOME_KEYRING_PID="1758"
 declare -x GPGKEY="0x65091615C98A3808"
 declare -x GPG_AGENT_INFO="/run/user/markmc/keyring-UiPefJ/gpg:0:1"

to end up in an image. Sure it's not sensitive (that's why I'm happy to paste it here) but it's still not the sort of stuff you'd feel comfortable being put into an image you might share with others. It will certainly come as a surprise to people, and it came as a surprise to me.

Reproducible builds is, of course, important and capturing any env variable which has an influence over the build would be great ... but capturing all just seems very wrong.'}, {'account_id': 1726, 'date': '2013-12-03 08:05:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with Mark, it's ok to capture env variables, but there is too much garbage been stored."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-04 01:15:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

This is missing the change-id; https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59622/ is where we should address this.'}]

commit_message:
Revert "Store DIB_* only env variables"

This reverts commit 7c2d1b2295fb2f6f92896795e36f8f49e6f7d55a

We want to capture aggressively to aid reproducability and diagnosing issues. Environment variables are not suitable storage for credentials, it's not up to us to police that.

commit_message:
Inline Table editing

Implementation of inline-table-editing blueprint:

- Design from jcoufal is implemented with Bootstrap elements.
- Inline edit mode implemented, Django Form Field connected to table
  logic, using Django Form Widget to render. Table Cell can be updated
  and refreshed.
- Allowed method implemented for checking of cell edit permissions
- Validation process is taken from Django Form Field logic, so
  validation is defined as part of Django Form Field defined in table
  Column.
- Update method of the cell is defined as Table Action. For obtaining
  row data, UpdateRow functionality is used.
- Horizon Tests for inline editing implemented.
- Selenium Tests for inline editing of tenants implemented
- Documentation written in both ref and topics

Change-Id: Ib29b58da71d3a8abc9688bc942fe49917161e97a
Implements: blueprint inline-table-editing

commit_message:
Add unit tests for volume reserve and unreserve

This adds unit tests for successful reserving and unreserving, and vice
versa for not being in the right status.

Change-Id: Iaa777055315251efa4a14976e25b9baab222f934

'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-10-27 16:50:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Is there a rough estimate on the impact of this new check on the time taken to complete the sync loop?'}, {'account_id': 2583, 'date': '2013-10-28 10:33:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Impact on time for sync loop will be significant. It will also grow with the number of networks. Maybe we should spawn a separate process instead of using _periodic_resync_helper()?'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-10-28 19:11:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with Salvatore, this is very expensive. Instead of polling wouldn't it be better if we registered a handler for the parent process to receive sigterm/sigkill events for children processes? The handler can then bring the child process back up. This would be a lot more efficient."}, {'account_id': 2583, 'date': '2013-10-29 13:46:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I agree with both of you of course. Setting WIP until I come up with better solution.'}, {'account_id': 2583, 'date': '2013-10-29 13:47:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-06 06:03:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-06 06:03:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2013-11-15 21:07:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm not certain that the signal handler idea will fly but I could be wrong.  I'm just thinking here...

In my experience, dnsmasq's parent is typically always 1.  I'm not sure that we want the parent process to be the agent because we don't want agent errors, restarts, etc. to affect the operation of a running dnsmasq.

Even if that weren't the case, if the agent goes down, the dnsmasq processes continue to run (I hope).  They would be orphaned and become child processes of init.  When the agent comes back up, dnsmasq is no longer a child.

Could eventlets be spawned?  Would that mitigate the impact of this change on the polling time?"}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-12-04 00:32:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Just chiming in, I actually do think you want dnsmasq to be interrupted if the dhcp agent has an error. It may very well be providing faulty information to network clients if the dhcp agent has gone away and isn't there to inform it of updates to its configuration. So if the agent goes down in flames, so should dnsmasq.

The idea is to keep _the agent_ running, not just dnsmasq. Let normal process HA do the rest.

Polling is not needed. Just spawn in foreground, handle SIGCHLD or wait() in a greenthread, and let good old Unix parent/child semantics clean things up.

Note that I've proposed a refactoring that would also address this in a bug I filed today:

https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1257524"}]

commit_message:
Start dnsmasq if it failed for some reason

Idea is to start dnsmasq if it was killed or stopped
for some reason. This is done within periodic_resync_helper.

Change-Id: I0217a0208d0797c67ca6d5cfdadf8c32443aa17f
Closes-Bug: 1244783
Co-Authored-By: Hirofumi Ichihara <ichihara.hirofumi@lab.ntt.co.jp>

commit_message:
If no block devices abort deployment

Based on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56525

Make the deployment to abort immediately in case the block devices are
not available.

Change-Id: Id1a23578b0e6c7f69bbf6e5a76f3e42f37980ba6
Partial-Bug: #1251525

commit_message:
Restrict sort_keys for stack lists

We are only allowing users to sort stacks on a subset of columns that
are known to be indexed.  Currently allowed sort columns are:

created_at
updated_at
name
status

Change-Id: Ib4f955336edd7d86a1b6bf98e38378b0d495d0dd
Closes-Bug: 1252116

As for the functionality with image property quotas, I had talked to a few folks including Mark. It is intended that the resulting transaction for image properties must be under the quota. I would love to discuss this further on IRC but this particular patch should not be affected.

commit_message:
Add config option to limit image tags

This patch adds the image_tag_quota config option. This allows a deployer
to limit the number of image tags allowed on an image for v2. The default value
is 128. If an image is somehow over the limit, tags can still be removed but no
more may be added.

Fixes bug 1252337
docImpact

Change-Id: I2036e2a88601d7c5aa85fad32d90fe0ed30b84c8

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw?

Change-Id: I5c70908e32fc5316e395c72810fc45f5db8a7a77
Closes-Bug: #1255864

commit_message:
Bump to using SQLAlchemy migrate 0.8.2

Requirements project has updated this to be able to remove a custom
check for sqlalchemy migrate 0.7.3 . Bumping this requirement will
let us do that.

NOTE: version 0.8.1 had a borked version number so
we require 0.8.2 or greater due to that.

Copied from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56662/

Change-Id: Id6548f275e237e1179bc6d3dcb2be1a37b14d351

commit_message:
Bump hacking to 0.8

Due to Bump hacking dependency is not the 0.8, some compatibility checks with python 3.x are not being done on gate and it is bringing code issues.
This commit has a change in order to keep compatibility with the rules added in hacking 0.8

Change-Id: I610f589af297c711be7fc52fd1b9a80b3275f7a3
Partial-Bug: #1257301

commit_message:
Bump to sqlalchemy-migrate 0.8.2

This allows us to drop some unsightly sqlalchemy-migrate 0.7.3
patching.

The related requirements change is here:

  Icde6248ca102884323d7912bab0f4a716aa294ec

Change-Id: I5f80dfc07f8256716d025002fc1a1f47e58b2142

commit_message:
Fix "in" comparisons with one element tuples

A single value enclosed in parentheses is not a tuple (it needs a comma
after the element) therefore the comparisons like 'if foo in ("bar")'
are wrong.

Closes-Bug: #1248443
Change-Id: I29a2227c9d83efc17ecfacc86d507d75edd4eaca

commit_message:
Revert "Don't call credentials_headers() twice"

When we create or update a stack, when deferred_auth_method=password
(which is the default in heat.conf), the client must pass the username
and password, even if they don't need to for authentication (ie
they're passing a token). Otherwise there's no username and password
in the context to store, and the engine validation in
heat/engine/service.py::_validate_deferred_auth_context fails.

No such issue exists when deferred_auth_method=trusts, which is why
this problem was missed during testing of the patch being reverted.

Note some fixup in addition to the revert was required to make the
tests pass, as ShellTestToken and ShellTestStandaloneToken now require
username/password set in the fake env.

This reverts commit a7ba3c323b16227e0ba2527f21bc89625f125234
Change-Id: I0e7bc3f748022c2bf5ef7ef6dfe4d97953e3fcab

commit_message:
Don't stop volume service for failed re-export operations

Commit b71570 "Set vol driver initialized before deleting volumes"
changed the manager behavior to call set_initialized() before
attempting to re-export volumes.

Drivers should not be considered initialized before re-export has
succeeded.  Otherwise a failure to export causes the volume
service to stop, when that failure should be handled like any other
failure to initialize.

Closes-Bug: 1257049
Related-Bug: 1232177
Change-Id: Ic6bc89ef3f15dbbc971fdd8c91117cccb5c2801b

I don't see much value in adding an API to provide this information.  I find it important to have a minimal API design.  The API itself is versioned.  That information should be sufficient with python-heatclient to access the needed functionality.

I will remove my -2 if the blueprint enters the "approved" state, indicating a general willingness on the part of the heat core to accept this api expansion into Heat.  Ping me on irc (sdake) if the blueprint enters approved and I haven't removed the -2 in a timely manner.

Recommended next step is to join our next irc meeting on Wednesday 2000 UTC and add the blueprint to the agenda:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/HeatAgenda

Regards
-steve'}, {'account_id': 9062, 'date': '2013-11-11 23:38:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Steven Hardy - What are your concerns around providing the release version without authentication?
If we move this /build_info endpoint into the API, the URL would end up being something like: "/v1/build_info".  We're not entirely opposed to it, but I think we would probably need to brainstorm an endpoint name that's less misleading since the build info is not specific to the version of the API (which is why we started it as a paste app).

@Steven Dake - Can you clarify whether you are against this change entirely or whether it just should not be put into the API?  The build version provides information on your current deployment of Heat rather than the API version; we believe that this information is valuable for anyone responsible for deploying Heat.

Examples:
1) You make changes not related to the API (e.g. configuration changes)
2) You're running the latest Heat source code (no official API version update)'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-11-12 02:50:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Steven Dake - Can you clarify whether you are against this change entirely or whether it just should not be put into the API? The build version provides information on your current deployment of Heat rather than the API version; we believe that this information is valuable for anyone responsible for deploying Heat.
Examples: 1) You make changes not related to the API (e.g. configuration changes) 2) You're running the latest Heat source code (no official API version update)

I auppose it is possible someone could be running from a specific git tag that is not a stable release, but I believe that would be dangerous in production.  Therefore I couldn't recommend it, and don't have a strong urge to enable it.

In any regard, seems like an odd addition to the API, which I think warrants further discussion in our weekly irc meeting if you wish to proceed with the patch."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-12 10:38:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Richard Lee: My concern is providing git-SHA level version information to anyone who requests it via a public API, without any authentication at all, as previously stated.  The (bad) implications of this seem pretty obvious to me:

1. You just made it trivial for any attacker to target the vulnerable Heat  service providers when their trunk-chasing or backports lag an upstream security fix, without even having to attempt exploiting the vulnerability.

2. Do you really want to provide every customer with a trivial way to anonymously monitor your compliance with any security related SLAs you may be contractually committed to?

Essentially this information is only useful to the service deployer, who already has this information anyway, e.g via package versions managed by whatever CM tool you manage your heat deployment with.

Also, what version are you even providing?  The API version (there may be multiple answers to this, if you're running a scaled-out environment with multiple API services, so the data will be a random response depending on what API service you hit), or the engine version (same problem)?

Basically I agree with sdake - I see little value to adding this to our API, and the method you propose here is unacceptable anyway, in my opinion."}, {'account_id': 9062, 'date': '2013-11-12 22:18:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-11-12 22:30:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

We need some discussion on whether we want this at all, but lets assume for the moment that we do.

It would be more useful to know the version of heat-engine rather than heat-api, so this would need an RPC call to retrieve the version.

Also until now we haven't considered any API changes that a deployer might choose to turn off via an extensions mechanism. This seems to qualify, so we need to write our extensions mechanism first."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-12 22:53:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Doesn't seem to work

Thanks for all the feedback.  After some discussion, we went with the paste app approach, but with the buildinfo middleware not active by default.  As another filter, this allows the configurability of making the endpoint available before auth, after auth, or not at all.

We think this all addresses the concerns mentioned so far and still provides the value we're trying to get out of it."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-11-13 00:34:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Ok so its a good point about wanting to know the version of the API as well as the engine separately even though they're currently packaged together, they certainly don't have to be. +1 adding build information for both.

WRT deployers wanting this or not, they should have several options including policy, paste.ini, or direct removal, so I don't think an entire new feature around features is warranted.

Regarding the need for the feature, I think that's been covered somewhat here. It would also be used as part of a status dashboard/monitoring system that allows folks responsible for actually running a live production Heat deployment to easily see what version of the service is running even if they aren't the people that have access to packaging and deployment information. Its also handy to have this info for bug reports, for example."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-11-13 00:34:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I would still like the default value to come from the version_info returned by whatever heat-engine responds to a build_info RPC call.

* implement an RPC build_info method
* in EngineService, check the value of heat.conf heat_version

  * for any other value of heat_version, return exactly that value
* default heat_version to be version_info
* document heat.conf.sample heat_version to describe the above behavior

It would be nice to document here what exactly pbr does. Chances are if the current revision is on a tag (which looks like a version string?) then pbr will use that and not append a git SHA.

Then, if deployers want to take advantage of version_info but don't want to leak git SHAs, all they need to do is incorporate git tagging into their deploy process. Unless deployers are continuously running trunk, they are probably doing something like this already."}, {'account_id': 9062, 'date': '2013-11-18 14:35:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

The version.version_info comes from heat/version.py which is `version_info = pbr.version.VersionInfo('heat')`.  This is what we were using to generate the release string initially.  This is our understanding of how release_string is generated (the documentation isn't as precise):

    PBR's current release information is very similar to git describe and
    is determined according to the following rules:

    1) Get version from setup.cfg (VERSION)
    2) Find the most recent annotated git tag object (TAG).
    3) Count the number of commits since TAG (X)
    4) Get the hash of the current commit (YYYYYY)

    The release information will be formatted in one of three possible ways:

    1) If TAG matches the current commit:
            release: TAG

    2) If VERSION is supplied in setup.cfg:
            release: VERSION.devX.gYYYYYY

    3) If a version is not provided:
            release: LAST_TAG.X.gYYYYYY

If the deployer does not tag each release, the git hash will be appended to the release name.  I'm hesitant to write logic that strips the hash out because I'm afraid of unintentionally stripping user defined tags (or writing overly complex logic to handle it).  For example, if a user tagged their release as "v1.1.grizzly", it would match the format of a PBR generated release string that we might strip.

Again, I'm open to using the pbr version as the default, but there seemed to be opposition to having a git hash out there as part of some default behavior.  If we're okay with a 'unknown' default for now, is it possible to get this in and continue the discussion of changing the default in a subsequent review?'}, {'account_id': 9062, 'date': '2013-11-18 14:36:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Rebased'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-11-18 14:36:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Like others, this whole concept gives me serious concerns about the type of security-related information we're prepared to give away to users, or even random members of the public. Back in the day Apache used to include version information in error pages by default... it no longer does that because it led to easy exploits of untold numbers of web servers.

I'm pleased to see that this issue has been somewhat mitigated. I think if cloud providers want to provide version numbers it's up to them to decide what numbers and what level of granularity they want to provide. However nothing should happen by default - there is a security tradeoff to be made, and that should be a conscious decision. The current patch addresses this issue (I mention it because any future patchsets need to maintain this property).

Remaining objections in order of increasing concern:

- The path is /build_info instead of /{tenant_id}/build_info. I realise this is intentional, but bear in mind that the endpoint in keystone includes the tenant_id part, so you have to go up a directory from the endpoint to get to this.
- This information seems fairly useless, in that there are likely to be multiple copies of heat-api and (in Icehouse) heat-engine running, the version of each copy may be different and obtaining the versions of a random-selected pair is not that interesting. In particular, if you experience an error you can't go and grab the versions of the API and Engine, because you may get completely different answers compared to what actually happened. So this can give you interesting answers or reliable answers, but never both.
- Configuring the version in heat.conf is more than a little odd. Generally if you install from a package you want the version to update; forcing a manual merge of configuration files is a sure way to guarantee that the version is usually wrong. Therefore the version should be stored in a separate file. Maybe /etc/heat/version. Packagers can decide what level of detail is appropriate to include in the file.
- Why is Heat the guinea pig for this? Surely having version numbers available by API is important for all services, or perhaps no services, but I can't see anything special about Heat that makes it the only service where the build version matters. I think you should raise this issue on the mailing list in the context of coming up with a scheme that can be used right across OpenStack, with supporting code in Oslo.

The last one is a show-stopper in my opinion, and I'm still contemplating -2 until that discussion happens."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-18 18:25:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

I think this is a great idea, however I do have some suggestions.

Right now this patch reads the heat_revision from the config file for the heat-api node and it's respective engine node. This is perfect for being combined with a build pipeline. You can build your heat package, write the heat revision, and deploy your code. Then you can hit each individual heat-api to figure out versions. This works rather well for canary deployments because you do have the ability to determine the version of each engine/api pair. Also, when combined with a CI/CD environment, this allows you to verify that a new version gets deployed.

I can see the point that the actual code running can be different that the version written to the config file, but that is very difficult to get around unless you rely on git, or write the version to python file.
I would be in support of a version.py, however I don't have a problem with the current implementation.

My -1 has to do with Zane's security problem. While I don't think showing the version to the end user is a huge deal, I do think we should have a configuration option to restrict calling this endpoint by ip range."}, {'account_id': 9062, 'date': '2013-11-22 00:45:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 9062, 'date': '2013-11-22 01:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

OK, that seems like an adequate way of handling the version config - a packager could arrange this to do the Right Thing... though I doubt many will.

Just to be clear, you understand that clients will have to access this with the path "../build-info", right? That seems wrong to me.

We should bump the API version to 1.1 if we're adding new functionality. Anybody know if we have to do this with every change, or roll them up and do it once per release?

Andrew:

> I do think we should have a configuration option to restrict calling this endpoint by ip range.

Keystone policy already provides for fine-grained role-based access control. IP restrictions are a non-standard and very blunt instrument by comparison.

> This works rather well for canary deployments because you do have the ability to determine the version of each engine/api pair.

You really don't. You may be able go behind the load balancer's back to get the version of a particular heat-api node, but the engine is chosen by the message queue and no correspondence will be entered into.'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-11-22 22:17:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

@zaneb: > Just to be clear, you understand that clients will have to access this with the path "../build-info", right? That seems wrong to me.

I know what you mean, but I think, given that this is the first of several non-tenant-scoped API paths, that we may want to consider an API version bump where we stop specifying the tenant in the endpoint/path.

I know there are some arguments for keeping it, but other projects mostly seem to be moving away from tenant/project ID's encoded in the path, and when we e.g do a stack-create, we're currently providing the tenant ID three times, once in the path, once in the request body, and again in the request context (due to the tenant scoped token).  That seems wrong too, to me.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:32:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I agree with zaneb that the path aspects of this are awkward, given that all/many current installation methods of heat result in the tenant_id encoded in the endpoint which ends up in the keystone service catalog.

IMO we should at least discuss an API version bump with an associated move to not specifying tenant_id in the endpoint for that version."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-25 18:38:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

FWIW this is not the first API that doesn't really need tenant scoping - the resource_types list doesn't need it either, but uses it anyway because it makes no sense to have a path starting with '../'.

IMO if we want to remove the tenant from the URL then we should do it for everything in a v2.0 API, not add/remove stuff piecemeal. [{'created': '2013-11-06 16:16:10.000000000', 'message': "Add middleware to query build information

This middleware captures requests to '/build_info' and uses PBR to
supply build information.

PBR's current release information is very similar to git describe and
is determined according to the following rules:

1) Get version from setup.cfg (VERSION)
2) Find the most recent annotated git tag object (TAG).
3) Count the number of commits since TAG (X)
4) Get the hash of the current commit (YYYYYY)

The release information will be formatted in one of three possible ways:

1) If TAG matches the current commit:
        release: TAG

2) If VERSION is supplied in setup.cfg:
        release: VERSION.devX.gYYYYYY

3) If a version is not provided:
        release: LAST_TAG.X.gYYYYYY

Implements: blueprint heat-build-info
Change-Id: Ibb2f5afda7c5d7c314e5e062d618405d9f4eb318

commit_message:
update to hacking 0.8

hacking 0.8 brings us a working H302 rule (should import modules
not objects) and a bunch of python 3 compat rules.

fix the python 3 compat issues to make this landable.

Change-Id: I53abf39394afc54da5ad049802dca0032f14882d

commit_message:
Use oslo-rootwrap in config directory names

Use oslo-rootwrap rather than oslo.rootwrap in directory names
(/etc/oslo-rootwrap and /usr/share/oslo-rootwrap), as suggested by
Chuck. Since this package is actually consumed through its binary
(oslo-rootwrap) rather than its library (oslo.rootwrap), this is
probably more appropriate.

Change-Id: I0e249d70937307b5fe116750923c20d487506c97

commit_message:
Add option to return disk usage report with byte suffix.

Disk usage is currently returned as bytes. This patch adds the option
to return the value with a more human-friendly suffix, eg. MB/GB/TB/PB.

Change-Id: I3d55181f7e6085e711bd6e09ea2ce0a12b290cc5

commit_message:
Utilites for manipulating base64 & PEM

Add two new utility modules

  - keystone.common.base64utils
  - keystone.common.pemutils

Add two new unit tests to exercise the above.

  - keystone.tests.test_base64utils
  - keystone.tests.test_pemutils

Functionality in these utilities will be utilized to fix bug #1233838
in a subsequent commit. It is hoped these modules will moved to Oslo
common code. Each module has a doc string describing their purpose and
functionalty.

Change-Id: I3546674dcd9eddec2c378929dd3f759f667cfd5d
Partial-Bug: #1233838

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-02 12:46:26.000000000', 'message': 'DB API and models for supporting Compute Hosts Reservations

As per our design doc for Hosts reservations [1], Climate needs to be
added three new models called ComputeHost, ComputeHostExtraCapabilities
and ComputeHostReservation

 * ComputeHost will store all info concerning hosts managed by Climate
   and will keep tracability on if they are free for a lease or not
 * ComputeHostExtraCapabilities will allow admin user to add extra info
   for each host to add to Climate like GPU or SSD which are not yet
   visible thru Nova-Compute
 * ComputeHostReservation will store all reservation details when
   creating a lease, needed by Manager when starting the lease

[1] : https://docs.google.com/drawings/d/1-_DOB65LsSGR4JUaPN525bWAg1yhvEv3KNcHfmuLvYw/edit

Change-Id: Ia1c6636fd8b324906139f35c0c49eb4abf6666f5

commit_message:
DB API and models for supporting Compute Hosts Reservations

As per our design doc for Hosts reservations [1], Climate needs to be
added three new models called ComputeHost, ComputeHostExtraCapabilities
and ComputeHostReservation

 * ComputeHost will store all info concerning hosts managed by Climate
   and will keep tracability on if they are free for a lease or not
 * ComputeHostExtraCapabilities will allow admin user to add extra info
   for each host to add to Climate like GPU or SSD which are not yet
   visible thru Nova-Compute
 * ComputeHostReservation will store all reservation details when
   creating a lease, needed by Manager when starting the lease

Implements bp:host-db-api

[1] : https://docs.google.com/drawings/d/1-_DOB65LsSGR4JUaPN525bWAg1yhvEv3KNcHfmuLvYw/edit

Change-Id: Ia1c6636fd8b324906139f35c0c49eb4abf6666f5

commit_message:
Docker Driver doesn't respect CPU limit

The docker driver doesn't respect the CPU settings of the configured
flavor.

Docker/LXC supports only relative cpu alloaction. The relative
cpu alloaction doesn't prevent that a container can use all CPUs but it
can at least insure that a container with more CPUs gets more CPU
cycles.

Change-Id: I7b299c1afd9c1269a07da4079c7272955a67822a
Closes-Bug: #1256264

commit_message:
Add more logging to migrate_volume_completion

Add a debug message on entering the function, and an info message if
it was called to clean up an error. This is useful because Nova copies
the data of in-use volumes, and if it fails there will only be a
message in the Nova logs.

Change-Id: I546d0bae8639072727ebe23394885d40255ba1d4

commit_message:
Use model_query() in db.*****_destroy

Use model_query() instead of session.query in db.volume_destroy,
db.volume_type_destroy, db.transfer_destroy and db.snapshot_destroy as
other methods use.
model_query function is the query helper which is used in most part of
cinder/db/sqlalchemy/api.py.

Change-Id: I97be252df9d40bb97231e3341d5cedec26af2d93
Closes-Bug: #1256483

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-30 19:19:51.000000000', 'message': 'Cisco nexus plugin fails to untrunk vlan if other hosts using vlan

Fixes bug 1246080

Without this fix, if two or more compute hosts have
instances which are
sharing a given VLAN on a Nexus switch, and then
all instances on one of the hosts which are using that
VLAN are terminated, while instances which are using
that VLAN on other hosts remain active, then
the VLAN is not being untrunked from the
corresponding interface on the Nexus switch as
expected.

This fix changes the VLAN removal logic from:
----If this the last instance using this VLAN on this switch:
--------untrunk the vlan from the switch interface
--------delete the VLAN from the switch
To:
----If this the last instance using this VLAN on this switch interface:
--------untrunk the vlan from the switch interface
--------If this the last instance using this VLAN on this switch:
------------delete the VLAN from the switch

Note that this bug also exists in the Cisco ML2
mechanism driver, but the code which implements
this is being redesigned, so it will be addressed for
the ML2 separately.

Change-Id: Icb1f95d1db4baa56c0f6fd68ce6342bbff27641d

--------If this the last instance using this VLAN on this switch:
------------delete the VLAN from the switch

Note that this bug also exists in the Cisco ML2
mechanism driver, but the code which implements
this is being redesigned, so it will be addressed for
the ML2 separately.

Change-Id: Icb1f95d1db4baa56c0f6fd68ce6342bbff27641d
'}]
commit_message:
Cisco nexus plugin fails to untrunk vlan if other hosts using vlan

Closes-Bug: #1246080

Without this fix, if two or more compute hosts have
instances which are
sharing a given VLAN on a Nexus switch, and then
all instances on one of the hosts which are using that
VLAN are terminated, while instances which are using
that VLAN on other hosts remain active, then
the VLAN is not being untrunked from the
corresponding interface on the Nexus switch as
expected.

This fix changes the VLAN removal logic from:
----If this the last instance using this VLAN on this switch:
--------untrunk the vlan from the switch interface
--------delete the VLAN from the switch
To:
----If this the last instance using this VLAN on this switch interface:
--------untrunk the vlan from the switch interface
--------If this the last instance using this VLAN on this switch:
------------delete the VLAN from the switch

Note that this bug also exists in the Cisco ML2
mechanism driver, but the code which implements
this is being redesigned, so it will be addressed for
the ML2 separately.

Change-Id: Icb1f95d1db4baa56c0f6fd68ce6342bbff27641d

commit_message:
Add default ctrl location for vol type encryption

This patch modifies the create requirements for the volume type
encryption API extension in cinder.  Currently, creating requires
that the "control location" be specified.  This patch provides
a default "control location" if none is specified, based on the
location of the provider.

Change-Id: Ia9178aa59b1b59a7fa0a5cef1989e5afcd512566
Implements: blueprint encrypt-cinder-volumes
DocImpact

Use mock in python3

python3 has mock in unittest, that lets us import it from
unittest.mock. The python2 case however needs to import mock

commit_message:
Adjust RBD delete log level

Set notice of volume no longer existing in RBD backend when attempting
to delete to log INFO level. Also move a comment next to related code.
This is a follow-up to suggestions from
3de7da12d1098ef777305099e5f4a039e536bf99.

Change-Id: I3ff854e0ead79e208106a371e14ec6ac7603d387

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-30 20:24:24.000000000', 'message': "Fix create_grant to raise NotFound if no user/group

The SQL assignment backend would not fail with NotFound if the
user or group didn't exist when calling create_grant while the
KVS assignment backend did fail.

It seems reasonable to check if the user or group exists when
creating a grant, so the SQL assignment backend is changed to also
check if the user or group exists.

Closes-Bug: #1239476
Change-Id: I2d3b2fd82e7d4d33ac7158968d72cbfbe37528dc
"}, {'created': '2013-10-30 22:02:26.000000000', 'message': "Fix KVS create_grant to not raise NotFound if no user/group

The KVS assigment backend would fail with NotFound if the user
or group didn't exist when calling create_grant while the SQL
assignment backend did not fail.

It's unreasonable to check if the user or group exists when
creating a grant, so the KVS assignment backend is changed to
not require the user or group to exist.

Closes-Bug: #1239476
Change-Id: I2d3b2fd82e7d4d33ac7158968d72cbfbe37528dc

assignment backend did not fail.

It's unreasonable to check if the user or group exists when
creating a grant, so the KVS assignment backend is changed to
not require the user or group to exist.

Closes-Bug: #1239476
Change-Id: I2d3b2fd82e7d4d33ac7158968d72cbfbe37528dc

commit_message:
Fix KVS create_grant to not raise NotFound if no user/group

The KVS assigment backend would fail with NotFound if the user
or group didn't exist when calling create_grant while the SQL
assignment backend did not fail.

It's unreasonable to check if the user or group exists when
creating a grant, so the KVS assignment backend is changed to
not require the user or group to exist.

Closes-Bug: #1239476
Change-Id: I2d3b2fd82e7d4d33ac7158968d72cbfbe37528dc

commit_message:
Enhance tests for assignment create_grant when no user or group

There were no tests that show the behavior of create_grant when
the user or group doesn't exist. Turns out the behavior is
different depending on the backend (sql vs kvs vs ldap).

Change-Id: I71c3e2b94aaa44e40c8a891b49cc2a9961cee16f
Related-Bug: #1239476

commit_message:
Add a Trait Type model and db table

The event api will provide a way to list all trait types for
a given event type. The current data model does not provide
an efficient way to get all trait types.

This change introduces a trait_type table, and TraitType model.
Trait information can be retrieved with this simple query into
TraitType:

SELECT id, desc, dtype FROM  trait_type;

The UniqueName table is no longer needed, so it has been removed.

Partial-Bug: 1211015
Change-Id: I6ec29dc1d71b5590204d7e7b1bf121c2c1ca1904

commit_message:
Dependency cleanup

Clean up dependency usage.

a) If the class uses a dependency directly, make sure it's
included (getting from superclass isn't enough)

b) If the class doesn't use a dependency directly, make
sure it's NOT included (being a superclass isn't excuse)

Change-Id: Ifbd489f349ec019a41093a2814664e6d8c9f0069

commit_message:
GreenDBConnection no longer assumes that arguments are kwargs

Previous this code assumed that almost all arguments would be passed
as kwargs. Now the code also handles ``timeout`` occurring in
``*args``. This is needed because on PyPy's sqlite module, they are
passed in ``*args``.

Change-Id: I7ce25e7b262c6f46680e3f0eb391094de8051946
